00:00:08.874 --> 00:00:16.280 align:middle line:90%


00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:19.370 align:middle line:10%
LISA GARR: Hi, I'm Lisa Garr,
host of "Gaiam Inspirations."

00:00:19.370 --> 00:00:23.050 align:middle line:10%
So what if you found out that
90 is the new middle age?

00:00:23.050 --> 00:00:26.790 align:middle line:10%
And what if we are not the
effect of our genetics at all

00:00:26.790 --> 00:00:29.720 align:middle line:10%
and we discovered how
to completely rewrite

00:00:29.720 --> 00:00:31.190 align:middle line:10%
our genetic code?

00:00:31.190 --> 00:00:33.440 align:middle line:10%
Well, some people currently
live their lives this way.

00:00:33.440 --> 00:00:36.500 align:middle line:84%
And joining me is one of
them, Dr. Mario Martinez.

00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:40.130 align:middle line:10%
Dr. Martinez is a clinical
neuropsychologist.

00:00:40.130 --> 00:00:43.250 align:middle line:10%
And he is the founder
of biocognitive science.

00:00:43.250 --> 00:00:46.580 align:middle line:10%
And he lectures worldwide
on how cultural beliefs

00:00:46.580 --> 00:00:50.480 align:middle line:10%
affect health and longevity
more than genetics.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:51.710 align:middle line:90%
Welcome to the show.

00:00:51.710 --> 00:00:51.810 align:middle line:90%
Thank you for being here.

00:00:51.810 --> 00:00:53.434 align:middle line:84%
DR MARIO MARTINEZ:
Pleasure to be here.

00:00:53.434 --> 00:00:56.310 align:middle line:84%
LISA: So what is
biocognitive science?

00:00:56.310 --> 00:00:58.830 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Biocognitive
science brings together

00:00:58.830 --> 00:01:01.970 align:middle line:10%
psychoneuroimmunology-- is an
area that studies how thoughts

00:01:01.970 --> 00:01:04.870 align:middle line:10%
and emotions affect the immune
system and other systems--

00:01:04.870 --> 00:01:07.760 align:middle line:10%
and anthropology,
how cultures shape

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:11.340 align:middle line:10%
are our beliefs about health,
wellness, and so forth.

00:01:11.340 --> 00:01:15.120 align:middle line:10%
But those two disciplines aren't
really speaking to each other.

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:19.550 align:middle line:10%
So what I did is I brought mind,
body, and culture together.

00:01:19.550 --> 00:01:21.770 align:middle line:84%
LISA: So give me an
example of how culture

00:01:21.770 --> 00:01:24.200 align:middle line:90%
affects somebody's genetics.

00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:27.230 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: All right,
for example, menopause.

00:01:27.230 --> 00:01:30.380 align:middle line:10%
Menopause has been turned
to an illness, and it's not.

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:32.840 align:middle line:10%
It's a process.

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:36.170 align:middle line:10%
In Peru and other
countries, the hot flashes

00:01:36.170 --> 00:01:39.029 align:middle line:10%
are called bochorno,
which means shame.

00:01:39.029 --> 00:01:41.320 align:middle line:10%
And we know now from research
in psychoneuroimmunology,

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:45.260 align:middle line:10%
the shame actually
causes inflammation.

00:01:45.260 --> 00:01:48.920 align:middle line:10%
So when you're shamed, you'll
have an inflammatory response.

00:01:48.920 --> 00:01:51.200 align:middle line:10%
So women in Peru, because
they call it shame

00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:54.980 align:middle line:10%
and the culture sees it a
shame, have a very high level

00:01:54.980 --> 00:01:56.960 align:middle line:10%
of inflammation during
their menopause,

00:01:56.960 --> 00:01:58.850 align:middle line:10%
especially with the hot flashes.

00:01:58.850 --> 00:02:01.280 align:middle line:10%
Go to another culture,
you go to Japan.

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:03.560 align:middle line:10%
And in Japan, the menopause
and the hot flashes

00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:07.130 align:middle line:10%
are called the second spring,
an opportunity for a woman

00:02:07.130 --> 00:02:10.160 align:middle line:10%
to gain more power in
the sense of respect,

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:14.090 align:middle line:10%
to be a resource for wisdom.

00:02:14.090 --> 00:02:15.770 align:middle line:10%
They don't have
the inflammation.

00:02:15.770 --> 00:02:16.580 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Interesting.

00:02:16.580 --> 00:02:18.770 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: So your culture
will shape the biology

00:02:18.770 --> 00:02:19.920 align:middle line:90%
to a certain degree.

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:21.740 align:middle line:10%
LISA: In the
experience that you've

00:02:21.740 --> 00:02:24.640 align:middle line:10%
had with training people
all around the world

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:31.130 align:middle line:10%
and blending that gap between
neurocognitive science

00:02:31.130 --> 00:02:33.470 align:middle line:10%
and their culture,
what do you think

00:02:33.470 --> 00:02:37.174 align:middle line:10%
is the biggest break down
with people in their cultures?

00:02:37.174 --> 00:02:38.840 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Well, I
think that the problem

00:02:38.840 --> 00:02:41.660 align:middle line:10%
is that people think that,
for example, the medicine is

00:02:41.660 --> 00:02:45.140 align:middle line:10%
the same everywhere, that
if you have an infection

00:02:45.140 --> 00:02:47.000 align:middle line:10%
you just need an
antibiotic everywhere.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:48.720 align:middle line:10%
It's not like that at all.

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:51.890 align:middle line:10%
In the United States,
the cause that's

00:02:51.890 --> 00:02:56.570 align:middle line:10%
given to migraines is vascular,
but if you go to the UK

00:02:56.570 --> 00:02:57.680 align:middle line:10%
is gastrointestinal.

00:02:57.680 --> 00:02:59.930 align:middle line:10%
If you go to France, it's liver.

00:02:59.930 --> 00:03:02.330 align:middle line:10%
So even medicine
has a way of going

00:03:02.330 --> 00:03:05.360 align:middle line:10%
into the system,
one with vascular,

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:07.040 align:middle line:10%
the other one with
the gastrointestinal.

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:08.090 align:middle line:10%
And what happens
to the migraines

00:03:08.090 --> 00:03:09.756 align:middle line:10%
probably has effects
on different parts,

00:03:09.756 --> 00:03:12.179 align:middle line:10%
but the culture decides where
to go in to take care of it.

00:03:12.179 --> 00:03:13.970 align:middle line:10%
LISA: I wonder which
one is more effective.

00:03:13.970 --> 00:03:15.500 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: They're all as
effective because what

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:17.240 align:middle line:10%
happened-- that's
a great question--

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:19.460 align:middle line:10%
because what makes
it so effective

00:03:19.460 --> 00:03:22.790 align:middle line:10%
is the placebo effect, as
well as the biochemistry.

00:03:22.790 --> 00:03:27.080 align:middle line:10%
If you get, what I call the
culture editors, a doctor

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:28.880 align:middle line:10%
in a clinic, a mother at home--

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:29.140 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Cultural editors--

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:31.681 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: And it's telling you
that that cultural editor will

00:03:31.681 --> 00:03:34.010 align:middle line:10%
say this is really
very good for you,

00:03:34.010 --> 00:03:35.990 align:middle line:10%
and it works, because
you have biochemistry,

00:03:35.990 --> 00:03:38.700 align:middle line:10%
but you also have the belief
system from an authority.

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:42.320 align:middle line:84%
And that kicks in
right the healing value

00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:44.717 align:middle line:90%
that we all have to self-heal.

00:03:44.717 --> 00:03:47.300 align:middle line:10%
LISA: I wonder if the opposite
happens where you don't believe

00:03:47.300 --> 00:03:51.140 align:middle line:10%
that medicine is going to help
you and you're told it is,

00:03:51.140 --> 00:03:54.360 align:middle line:10%
but if you don't personally
believe it, it's not going to,

00:03:54.360 --> 00:03:55.160 align:middle line:10%
is it?

00:03:55.160 --> 00:03:56.826 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: You'll fight
it, that's right.

00:03:56.826 --> 00:03:58.886 align:middle line:84%
And even worse will
be the nocebo effect--

00:03:58.886 --> 00:04:00.260 align:middle line:84%
would be the
opposite of placebo.

00:04:00.260 --> 00:04:01.370 align:middle line:90%
I shall heel.

00:04:01.370 --> 00:04:03.050 align:middle line:90%
I shall harm is nocebo.

00:04:03.050 --> 00:04:04.800 align:middle line:10%
You're told you have
six months to live.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:05.600 align:middle line:10%
That's nocebo.

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:06.808 align:middle line:10%
You're being sentenced there.

00:04:06.808 --> 00:04:08.120 align:middle line:10%
That's not good science.

00:04:08.120 --> 00:04:10.490 align:middle line:10%
That's based on averages.

00:04:10.490 --> 00:04:15.510 align:middle line:10%
And when they look at the curve,
the normal curve, that illness,

00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:17.550 align:middle line:10%
you may have six months
to live on the average.

00:04:17.550 --> 00:04:20.089 align:middle line:10%
But if you look at the other
side of the tail with the tail

00:04:20.089 --> 00:04:23.220 align:middle line:10%
at the end, the people who
live 7 years, 10 years,

00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:24.410 align:middle line:10%
they don't look at that.

00:04:24.410 --> 00:04:26.060 align:middle line:10%
They consider that
a nuisance variable.

00:04:26.060 --> 00:04:28.160 align:middle line:10%
They only look at the middle.

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:32.720 align:middle line:10%
So you're being sentence with
a science that is not really

00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:34.857 align:middle line:10%
as accurate as they're saying.

00:04:34.857 --> 00:04:36.440 align:middle line:10%
LISA: That so needs
to change, though,

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:40.820 align:middle line:10%
because the doctors are saying
these statistics to protect

00:04:40.820 --> 00:04:42.030 align:middle line:10%
themselves legally.

00:04:42.030 --> 00:04:42.830 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:04:42.830 --> 00:04:44.210 align:middle line:84%
LISA: And they
have an obligation

00:04:44.210 --> 00:04:47.270 align:middle line:90%
to be able to state the facts.

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:50.900 align:middle line:10%
But I don't think there is an
awareness on the damage that

00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:52.651 align:middle line:10%
is done when that death
sentence is given.

00:04:52.651 --> 00:04:53.483 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Of course.

00:04:53.483 --> 00:04:54.560 align:middle line:90%
You can do it ethically.

00:04:54.560 --> 00:04:57.770 align:middle line:84%
You could say on the average
people live six months.

00:04:57.770 --> 00:05:00.710 align:middle line:84%
Now we know of many
cases that live 10 years.

00:05:00.710 --> 00:05:04.070 align:middle line:10%
What we need to do is, what
can we learn from those people

00:05:04.070 --> 00:05:06.620 align:middle line:10%
those people using
the causes of health?

00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:09.380 align:middle line:10%
The people that
die early are using

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:11.470 align:middle line:10%
the learning of an illness.

00:05:11.470 --> 00:05:12.630 align:middle line:10%
Illnesses are learned.

00:05:12.630 --> 00:05:13.430 align:middle line:10%
So that--

00:05:13.430 --> 00:05:14.390 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Illnesses are learned?

00:05:14.390 --> 00:05:15.020 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: I think so.

00:05:15.020 --> 00:05:16.394 align:middle line:10%
I think there's
some-- of course,

00:05:16.394 --> 00:05:18.180 align:middle line:10%
there are 2%, 3%
of illnesses that

00:05:18.180 --> 00:05:23.040 align:middle line:10%
are genetically already
set as an expression

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:25.620 align:middle line:10%
of a mistake, a genetic mistake.

00:05:25.620 --> 00:05:27.780 align:middle line:10%
But that's 2%, 3%.

00:05:27.780 --> 00:05:32.100 align:middle line:10%
The rest, your immune
system is consistently

00:05:32.100 --> 00:05:34.770 align:middle line:10%
relentlessly trying to
keep you healthy, rather

00:05:34.770 --> 00:05:36.250 align:middle line:10%
than the other way around.

00:05:36.250 --> 00:05:38.010 align:middle line:10%
What we learn is we
learn to get sick.

00:05:38.010 --> 00:05:38.940 align:middle line:10%
Not to blame.

00:05:38.940 --> 00:05:39.981 align:middle line:10%
You don't blame yourself.

00:05:39.981 --> 00:05:41.220 align:middle line:10%
But you learn to get sick.

00:05:41.220 --> 00:05:45.120 align:middle line:10%
If, for example, it
was functional for you

00:05:45.120 --> 00:05:48.657 align:middle line:10%
to be very passive and
take on a lot of abuse,

00:05:48.657 --> 00:05:50.240 align:middle line:10%
well, that was
functional at the time.

00:05:50.240 --> 00:05:52.600 align:middle line:10%
You don't get sick, because
this is a preservation.

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:55.110 align:middle line:10%
But let's say 10 years
you keep doing that.

00:05:55.110 --> 00:05:58.470 align:middle line:10%
You have created a
deficient immune system,

00:05:58.470 --> 00:06:01.170 align:middle line:10%
because you're responding
from helplessness.

00:06:01.170 --> 00:06:03.680 align:middle line:10%
That deficient immune
system, you can pick up

00:06:03.680 --> 00:06:08.020 align:middle line:10%
whatever is going on, whatever
pre-cancer cells to infections.

00:06:08.020 --> 00:06:11.160 align:middle line:10%
So you're teaching a system
to be deficient if you're

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:13.060 align:middle line:10%
deficient by your behavior.

00:06:13.060 --> 00:06:13.860 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Interesting.

00:06:13.860 --> 00:06:18.600 align:middle line:10%
So in a sense, that's
what the cultural behavior

00:06:18.600 --> 00:06:22.500 align:middle line:10%
is learning a
culture of sickness

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:24.540 align:middle line:10%
rather than learning
a culture of wellness.

00:06:24.540 --> 00:06:26.010 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Yes, exactly.

00:06:26.010 --> 00:06:28.770 align:middle line:10%
LISA: You shared with me that
you work with certain Fortune

00:06:28.770 --> 00:06:32.040 align:middle line:10%
100 companies with the
executives at the companies

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:35.340 align:middle line:10%
on how not to burn
themselves out health-wise

00:06:35.340 --> 00:06:40.230 align:middle line:10%
as making dozens and
dozens of decisions a day.

00:06:40.230 --> 00:06:41.892 align:middle line:10%
How do you teach
them to do that?

00:06:41.892 --> 00:06:44.100 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: What I teach them--
and at first they think

00:06:44.100 --> 00:06:46.537 align:middle line:10%
I'm just coming from Mars--

00:06:46.537 --> 00:06:48.120 align:middle line:10%
and I tell them I'm
going to teach you

00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:50.850 align:middle line:10%
how to make decisions
in your organization

00:06:50.850 --> 00:06:52.454 align:middle line:10%
like the immune system does.

00:06:52.454 --> 00:06:54.870 align:middle line:10%
The immune system makes hundreds
of thousands of decisions

00:06:54.870 --> 00:06:58.740 align:middle line:10%
a second without
centralized brain function.

00:06:58.740 --> 00:06:59.780 align:middle line:10%
LISA: OK, automatically?

00:06:59.780 --> 00:07:00.780 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Automatically.

00:07:00.780 --> 00:07:02.790 align:middle line:10%
Because what the
immune system does

00:07:02.790 --> 00:07:04.860 align:middle line:10%
is if you have an
infection somewhere,

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:08.190 align:middle line:10%
whatever molecule or whatever
cell from the immune system

00:07:08.190 --> 00:07:10.890 align:middle line:10%
is taking care of it, that
becomes the local brain.

00:07:10.890 --> 00:07:13.470 align:middle line:10%
It becomes the
local intelligence.

00:07:13.470 --> 00:07:15.810 align:middle line:10%
And then when it can't
do anything more,

00:07:15.810 --> 00:07:17.520 align:middle line:10%
then it'll call in
whatever it needs.

00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:19.710 align:middle line:84%
And that's called the
distributed control.

00:07:19.710 --> 00:07:22.290 align:middle line:10%
That simple
decision-making process,

00:07:22.290 --> 00:07:24.710 align:middle line:10%
decentralized and local
intelligence and distributed

00:07:24.710 --> 00:07:27.300 align:middle line:10%
control changes not
only the creativity

00:07:27.300 --> 00:07:31.170 align:middle line:10%
and the productivity, but it
changes the greatest problem

00:07:31.170 --> 00:07:33.480 align:middle line:10%
we have in corporate America
and corporate world is

00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:34.990 align:middle line:10%
chronic illnesses.

00:07:34.990 --> 00:07:38.910 align:middle line:84%
LISA: With the executives,
with hypertension and all that,

00:07:38.910 --> 00:07:39.930 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:07:39.930 --> 00:07:42.263 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: Because what's
happening is what's making them

00:07:42.263 --> 00:07:43.890 align:middle line:90%
sick is not the stressful job--

00:07:43.890 --> 00:07:45.820 align:middle line:90%
stress can be good or bad--

00:07:45.820 --> 00:07:48.420 align:middle line:84%
it's the organizational
culture that they create

00:07:48.420 --> 00:07:49.820 align:middle line:90%
that causes helplessness.

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:51.570 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Well, it's
interesting because we're

00:07:51.570 --> 00:07:54.670 align:middle line:10%
moving in such a
faster paced world now.

00:07:54.670 --> 00:07:56.080 align:middle line:10%
And it's just
getting get faster.

00:07:56.080 --> 00:07:56.880 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:07:56.880 --> 00:07:58.290 align:middle line:10%
LISA: So it's
almost like we need

00:07:58.290 --> 00:08:01.690 align:middle line:10%
to be super humans to catch
up with the pace of business

00:08:01.690 --> 00:08:02.604 align:middle line:10%
these days.

00:08:02.604 --> 00:08:04.020 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: Well,
in a way, what you

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:06.269 align:middle line:84%
want to do is you want to
be able to be mindful, to be

00:08:06.269 --> 00:08:07.620 align:middle line:90%
selective of the information.

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:12.060 align:middle line:10%
An example, attention deficit
disorder, it's not a disorder.

00:08:12.060 --> 00:08:14.510 align:middle line:10%
It's been turned into
an illness and it's not.

00:08:14.510 --> 00:08:16.260 align:middle line:10%
And I know the
neurochemistry and whatnot.

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:21.074 align:middle line:10%
What it is is that these kids
have abundance of curiosity--

00:08:21.074 --> 00:08:21.990 align:middle line:10%
LISA: And creativity--

00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:23.031 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: And creativity.

00:08:23.031 --> 00:08:24.750 align:middle line:84%
So you have to set
up the environment

00:08:24.750 --> 00:08:26.230 align:middle line:90%
to increase the novelty.

00:08:26.230 --> 00:08:28.500 align:middle line:10%
But the classrooms
aren't set up for them.

00:08:28.500 --> 00:08:31.050 align:middle line:10%
So it's better to medicate
and create a little zombie

00:08:31.050 --> 00:08:33.409 align:middle line:10%
than treat it appropriately.

00:08:33.409 --> 00:08:35.400 align:middle line:10%
LISA: They're set up
for be quiet an listen.

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:36.200 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:37.770 align:middle line:10%
And these kids get
bored because they

00:08:37.770 --> 00:08:40.080 align:middle line:10%
have an abundance of novelty.

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:41.500 align:middle line:10%
LISA: And they
don't have any say.

00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:42.916 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: They
don't have any say.

00:08:42.916 --> 00:08:44.890 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Yeah, they're
told not to talk.

00:08:44.890 --> 00:08:47.020 align:middle line:10%
OK, there's a couple of
slides that we have here.

00:08:47.020 --> 00:08:49.290 align:middle line:10%
And this particular
slide, you say

00:08:49.290 --> 00:08:53.280 align:middle line:10%
that most illnesses are learned
and the causes of health

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:54.540 align:middle line:10%
are inherited.

00:08:54.540 --> 00:08:56.440 align:middle line:10%
What do you mean by that?

00:08:56.440 --> 00:08:58.920 align:middle line:10%
We've kind of been
talking about this.

00:08:58.920 --> 00:09:01.350 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: We're born with
tremendous resilience.

00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:03.990 align:middle line:10%
We're born with a
system that knows

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:08.970 align:middle line:10%
how to pick up on foreign bodies
without even you knowing it,

00:09:08.970 --> 00:09:10.950 align:middle line:10%
because they're
fighting constantly.

00:09:10.950 --> 00:09:15.240 align:middle line:84%
So we're already set up with all
the causes that create health.

00:09:15.240 --> 00:09:16.780 align:middle line:90%
We're already born with it.

00:09:16.780 --> 00:09:19.650 align:middle line:84%
It's in our DNA, and it's
expressed through our genes.

00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:21.240 align:middle line:90%
The illnesses are learned--

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:22.980 align:middle line:84%
many illnesses, not
all, because some

00:09:22.980 --> 00:09:28.380 align:middle line:84%
are genetic, specifically
genetic, but very low percent.

00:09:28.380 --> 00:09:31.500 align:middle line:84%
The rest is our behavior,
our belief systems,

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:34.200 align:middle line:84%
our way of doing
things, the behavior

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:35.940 align:middle line:90%
is teaching the immune system.

00:09:35.940 --> 00:09:37.370 align:middle line:84%
It's teaching the
nervous system.

00:09:37.370 --> 00:09:38.786 align:middle line:84%
It's teaching the
endocrine system

00:09:38.786 --> 00:09:41.370 align:middle line:84%
to function based on the
consciousness that we live.

00:09:41.370 --> 00:09:43.300 align:middle line:84%
So I'll give you an
example, fibromyalgia,

00:09:43.300 --> 00:09:45.300 align:middle line:90%
which is very common now.

00:09:45.300 --> 00:09:48.840 align:middle line:84%
Fibromyalgia, the most of
the problem of fibromyalgia

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:52.860 align:middle line:84%
is that you have a sleep
deficit in delta, delta sleep.

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:56.480 align:middle line:84%
And delta is where the
immune system does a repair.

00:09:56.480 --> 00:10:03.780 align:middle line:84%
The pituitary release of some
of the human health hormones.

00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:07.620 align:middle line:84%
And that's what does the
repair and increases the energy

00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:09.210 align:middle line:90%
in the cells and all that.

00:10:09.210 --> 00:10:11.280 align:middle line:84%
So you learned to
be hyper vigilant.

00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:14.720 align:middle line:84%
You learned to be very cautious
when you were a little girl

00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:16.220 align:middle line:84%
because grandpa
would come in and do

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:18.620 align:middle line:84%
something that was inappropriate
when you were sleeping.

00:10:18.620 --> 00:10:21.090 align:middle line:84%
So I had an initial
function of wisdom.

00:10:21.090 --> 00:10:21.890 align:middle line:90%
LISA: I see.

00:10:21.890 --> 00:10:24.484 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: You had to
learn to be hypervigilant.

00:10:24.484 --> 00:10:26.150 align:middle line:84%
What happens when
you're hyper vigilant?

00:10:26.150 --> 00:10:29.330 align:middle line:84%
You teach your nervous system
to also be hypervigilant.

00:10:29.330 --> 00:10:31.750 align:middle line:10%
You teach your immune system
to be deficient because you

00:10:31.750 --> 00:10:33.050 align:middle line:10%
are being hypervigilant.

00:10:33.050 --> 00:10:35.780 align:middle line:10%
It works because it has a
function of preservation.

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:39.400 align:middle line:10%
You wait 10 years when
grandpa is no longer there.

00:10:39.400 --> 00:10:40.790 align:middle line:84%
You've taught your
nervous system

00:10:40.790 --> 00:10:44.930 align:middle line:84%
to create chronic pain with
the primary pain receptors.

00:10:44.930 --> 00:10:48.800 align:middle line:84%
You taught your immune system
to be deficient because it's not

00:10:48.800 --> 00:10:50.480 align:middle line:90%
getting the delta sleep.

00:10:50.480 --> 00:10:52.100 align:middle line:84%
And you taught your
endocrine system

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:54.740 align:middle line:84%
to release
pro-inflammatory products.

00:10:54.740 --> 00:10:58.610 align:middle line:84%
So you taught the system
fibromyalgia-- not to blame--

00:10:58.610 --> 00:10:59.960 align:middle line:90%
but that's what you taught it.

00:10:59.960 --> 00:11:02.330 align:middle line:84%
The good news is if you learn
something, you can unlearn it.

00:11:02.330 --> 00:11:02.840 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Unlearn it.

00:11:02.840 --> 00:11:04.465 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: You can
unlearn fibromyalgia.

00:11:04.465 --> 00:11:07.340 align:middle line:84%
LISA: And so in effect it's as
if the grandfather is always

00:11:07.340 --> 00:11:08.660 align:middle line:90%
there.

00:11:08.660 --> 00:11:10.630 align:middle line:84%
That's the way that
the brain is working.

00:11:10.630 --> 00:11:15.780 align:middle line:84%
But you can reverse that
through things like awareness,

00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:18.650 align:middle line:84%
but also through what you talk
about in terms of the mind body

00:11:18.650 --> 00:11:18.950 align:middle line:90%
code.

00:11:18.950 --> 00:11:19.750 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:11:19.750 --> 00:11:23.340 align:middle line:10%
LISA: So we have here a slide
of the cover of "The Mind Body

00:11:23.340 --> 00:11:24.140 align:middle line:10%
Code."

00:11:24.140 --> 00:11:28.310 align:middle line:10%
This particular picture
that we're looking at here

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:30.140 align:middle line:10%
is the cover of
your CD set, right?

00:11:30.140 --> 00:11:30.940 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:34.400 align:middle line:10%
LISA: OK, what is
the mind body code?

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:38.090 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: I studied two
very unusual populations--

00:11:38.090 --> 00:11:40.580 align:middle line:84%
centenarians, people
who are over 100,

00:11:40.580 --> 00:11:43.730 align:middle line:84%
but healthy centenarians,
not centenarians who are

00:11:43.730 --> 00:11:46.350 align:middle line:90%
vegetating and in bad shape.

00:11:46.350 --> 00:11:48.770 align:middle line:84%
And I found that
their genetics is only

00:11:48.770 --> 00:11:51.180 align:middle line:84%
about the genetic
contribution to the longevity.

00:11:51.180 --> 00:11:54.170 align:middle line:90%
So maybe 20% top.

00:11:54.170 --> 00:11:57.620 align:middle line:84%
Another very interesting group
of people, very, very unusual

00:11:57.620 --> 00:12:02.900 align:middle line:84%
are the people with stigmata,
who have the wounds of Christ.

00:12:02.900 --> 00:12:05.430 align:middle line:84%
And they're only the
Catholics-- see the culture.

00:12:05.430 --> 00:12:09.520 align:middle line:84%
And when you find a legitimate
stigmatic, 1 out of 100--

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:12.080 align:middle line:84%
and there've only been about
380 since Saint Francis

00:12:12.080 --> 00:12:14.900 align:middle line:90%
and the 13th century--

00:12:14.900 --> 00:12:18.770 align:middle line:84%
you find that these people
have a hyperimmunity.

00:12:18.770 --> 00:12:20.990 align:middle line:84%
And people around them,
if they're Catholic,

00:12:20.990 --> 00:12:23.600 align:middle line:90%
will have spontaneous healing.

00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:24.980 align:middle line:90%
So that's a mind body code.

00:12:24.980 --> 00:12:27.500 align:middle line:84%
That is by believing
something, you

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:31.060 align:middle line:84%
trigger something that is
transbiological in a sense.

00:12:31.060 --> 00:12:35.420 align:middle line:84%
One for National Geographic had
a woman who had the stigmata,

00:12:35.420 --> 00:12:40.670 align:middle line:84%
and a man was cured, total
spontaneous remission,

00:12:40.670 --> 00:12:44.326 align:middle line:84%
of prostate cancer, and
a little boy of leukemia.

00:12:44.326 --> 00:12:46.700 align:middle line:84%
And I followed up with their
physician nine months later,

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:47.690 align:middle line:90%
no symptoms.

00:12:47.690 --> 00:12:48.520 align:middle line:84%
LISA: Oh, my
goodness, we're going

00:12:48.520 --> 00:12:51.090 align:middle line:84%
to take a look at that National
Geographic piece in a minute.

00:12:51.090 --> 00:12:51.890 align:middle line:90%
Fascinating.

00:12:51.890 --> 00:12:53.510 align:middle line:90%
So they have hyperimmunity.

00:12:53.510 --> 00:12:56.180 align:middle line:84%
What about these particular
people, the centenarians?

00:12:56.180 --> 00:13:00.980 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: The centenarians they
defy what gerontology tells us,

00:13:00.980 --> 00:13:04.820 align:middle line:10%
that you go from
order to disorder,

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:06.465 align:middle line:10%
because we borrowed
them from physics.

00:13:06.465 --> 00:13:08.840 align:middle line:10%
That's good for carburetors
and planets and other things,

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:10.230 align:middle line:10%
but not for human beings.

00:13:10.230 --> 00:13:11.990 align:middle line:84%
We don't go from
order to disorder.

00:13:11.990 --> 00:13:14.460 align:middle line:90%
We go from simple to complex.

00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:17.770 align:middle line:84%
So what we think that's
becoming a deteriorating brain

00:13:17.770 --> 00:13:20.250 align:middle line:90%
is becoming a complex brain.

00:13:20.250 --> 00:13:22.610 align:middle line:10%
So these centenarians,
they don't

00:13:22.610 --> 00:13:26.360 align:middle line:10%
buy into what I call
the cultural portals--

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:33.200 align:middle line:10%
infancy, young adult, middle
age, third age or elderly.

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:38.900 align:middle line:10%
And without us knowing it, it's
so subtle, if you're 44 today,

00:13:38.900 --> 00:13:41.180 align:middle line:10%
you're pre-middle age.

00:13:41.180 --> 00:13:44.196 align:middle line:84%
But if the next day you're
45, you're middle age.

00:13:44.196 --> 00:13:45.320 align:middle line:90%
And you fall into a portal.

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:47.360 align:middle line:90%
You begin to dress middle age.

00:13:47.360 --> 00:13:49.250 align:middle line:90%
The car has to be middle age.

00:13:49.250 --> 00:13:51.020 align:middle line:84%
You have to be thinking
about retirement.

00:13:51.020 --> 00:13:54.060 align:middle line:84%
And that's what ages you
to the greatest degree.

00:13:54.060 --> 00:13:56.780 align:middle line:84%
LISA: So as I said earlier,
90 being the new middle age,

00:13:56.780 --> 00:13:59.030 align:middle line:84%
I got that from you
CD series, yeah.

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:01.040 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: And when you
ask a centenarian--

00:14:01.040 --> 00:14:02.660 align:middle line:84%
I'll ask them anywhere
in the world--

00:14:02.660 --> 00:14:03.530 align:middle line:90%
what's middle age?

00:14:03.530 --> 00:14:04.330 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:05.790 align:middle line:90%
I'll find out when I die.

00:14:05.790 --> 00:14:06.670 align:middle line:90%
They don't know.

00:14:06.670 --> 00:14:07.631 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Look backwards.

00:14:07.631 --> 00:14:09.380 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: And the worst
thing you could do

00:14:09.380 --> 00:14:12.145 align:middle line:10%
is go to an actuarial
and see this is my age

00:14:12.145 --> 00:14:13.770 align:middle line:10%
and this is how long
I'm going to live.

00:14:13.770 --> 00:14:15.000 align:middle line:10%
That's sentencing yourself.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:16.190 align:middle line:10%
That's not good science.

00:14:16.190 --> 00:14:18.466 align:middle line:84%
Those are probabilities,
but not sentencing.

00:14:18.466 --> 00:14:19.590 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Those are statistics.

00:14:19.590 --> 00:14:21.410 align:middle line:84%
So this particular
gentleman that you

00:14:21.410 --> 00:14:23.590 align:middle line:90%
have running here a marathon.

00:14:23.590 --> 00:14:25.290 align:middle line:10%
At what age is he?

00:14:25.290 --> 00:14:28.250 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: He ran
this marathon at 101.

00:14:28.250 --> 00:14:31.010 align:middle line:10%
And he started running
I believe in his 80s

00:14:31.010 --> 00:14:32.880 align:middle line:10%
because his son died.

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:35.970 align:middle line:84%
And in order to deal with
that, he started running.

00:14:35.970 --> 00:14:38.840 align:middle line:84%
And when you train your body,
your body will continue to run.

00:14:38.840 --> 00:14:40.390 align:middle line:90%
And then 101.

00:14:40.390 --> 00:14:41.190 align:middle line:90%
LISA: 101.

00:14:41.190 --> 00:14:43.022 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: He completed
the marathon.

00:14:43.022 --> 00:14:44.480 align:middle line:10%
LISA: And he started
running at 85.

00:14:44.480 --> 00:14:47.000 align:middle line:10%
So the ideas of the
joints not holding up

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.620 align:middle line:10%
for the long period of time,
he didn't have that thought.

00:14:49.620 --> 00:14:50.420 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: No.

00:14:50.420 --> 00:14:53.120 align:middle line:90%
And actually, your joints--

00:14:53.120 --> 00:14:54.537 align:middle line:90%
there's some damage.

00:14:54.537 --> 00:14:56.120 align:middle line:84%
I think swimming is
better in general.

00:14:56.120 --> 00:14:57.530 align:middle line:10%
But it will do some damage.

00:14:57.530 --> 00:15:00.410 align:middle line:10%
But what happens is that
what you're believing

00:15:00.410 --> 00:15:02.992 align:middle line:10%
and what you're doing,
you're being cautious

00:15:02.992 --> 00:15:04.700 align:middle line:10%
because another thing
about centenarians,

00:15:04.700 --> 00:15:05.616 align:middle line:10%
they're very cautious.

00:15:05.616 --> 00:15:07.920 align:middle line:84%
You don't find any
addictive centenarians.

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:09.230 align:middle line:90%
They're middle way.

00:15:09.230 --> 00:15:11.900 align:middle line:84%
They'll smoke a cigar
before they go to sleep,

00:15:11.900 --> 00:15:13.130 align:middle line:90%
but only a cigar.

00:15:13.130 --> 00:15:15.560 align:middle line:84%
And if you ask them, why
don't you smoke any more?

00:15:15.560 --> 00:15:16.920 align:middle line:90%
I only enjoy one.

00:15:16.920 --> 00:15:19.310 align:middle line:84%
And it's a ritual,
rather than a routine.

00:15:19.310 --> 00:15:24.170 align:middle line:10%
So this runner at 101 completed
the marathon actually.

00:15:24.170 --> 00:15:26.850 align:middle line:84%
LISA: Oh, my goodness, 20
something miles, 27 miles,

00:15:26.850 --> 00:15:27.650 align:middle line:90%
my goodness.

00:15:27.650 --> 00:15:28.760 align:middle line:90%
Now, this is funny.

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:30.650 align:middle line:84%
I mean now how many
of the centenarians

00:15:30.650 --> 00:15:31.700 align:middle line:90%
have a sense of humor?

00:15:31.700 --> 00:15:33.408 align:middle line:84%
This next picture is
actually terrifying.

00:15:33.408 --> 00:15:35.600 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: I would say
a very high percent.

00:15:35.600 --> 00:15:38.010 align:middle line:84%
This woman on her
100th birthday,

00:15:38.010 --> 00:15:40.400 align:middle line:84%
she just lit up a
cigarette with the candles.

00:15:40.400 --> 00:15:41.777 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Oh, does she smoke?

00:15:41.777 --> 00:15:42.860 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: She smoked, yes.

00:15:42.860 --> 00:15:44.260 align:middle line:90%
LISA: She and George Burns.

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:45.060 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:15:45.060 --> 00:15:47.730 align:middle line:84%
LISA: But you said they
don't take a lot of risks.

00:15:47.730 --> 00:15:49.910 align:middle line:90%
This particular one that was a--

00:15:49.910 --> 00:15:51.890 align:middle line:84%
every body is
different, who knows?

00:15:51.890 --> 00:15:53.960 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: Well,
they don't abuse.

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:56.140 align:middle line:10%
What they do is they do it in--

00:15:56.140 --> 00:15:59.376 align:middle line:10%
a ritual is something that
you do to identify who you are

00:15:59.376 --> 00:16:01.125 align:middle line:10%
and your culture and
to really enjoy like,

00:16:01.125 --> 00:16:05.600 align:middle line:10%
for example, a birthday,
going to an exalted place

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:07.460 align:middle line:10%
or religious place once a year.

00:16:07.460 --> 00:16:11.030 align:middle line:10%
Those things identify who
you are and your culture.

00:16:11.030 --> 00:16:14.644 align:middle line:10%
A Cuban centenarian,
this woman was about 103.

00:16:14.644 --> 00:16:17.060 align:middle line:84%
I asked her-- at first I would
think-- what's your secret?

00:16:17.060 --> 00:16:19.400 align:middle line:84%
And she said, well, I
have a little shot of rum

00:16:19.400 --> 00:16:20.870 align:middle line:84%
before I go to
sleep every night.

00:16:20.870 --> 00:16:23.250 align:middle line:84%
And I thought it's got to
be some quality of the run,

00:16:23.250 --> 00:16:24.740 align:middle line:84%
and not the rum
and not the cigar.

00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:27.680 align:middle line:84%
What I found is that
quality is in the ritual,

00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:29.430 align:middle line:90%
whatever you, do the ritual.

00:16:29.430 --> 00:16:34.170 align:middle line:84%
So she would have a shot of rum,
but she wasn't an alcoholic.

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:37.400 align:middle line:84%
She would drink the rum as a
ritual before going to sleep.

00:16:37.400 --> 00:16:39.215 align:middle line:84%
And that kind of
process, you're very

00:16:39.215 --> 00:16:40.340 align:middle line:90%
aware of what you're doing.

00:16:40.340 --> 00:16:42.740 align:middle line:10%
It's not habitual like
taking a shower, or driving

00:16:42.740 --> 00:16:44.180 align:middle line:10%
and you get some where and
you say, I can't believe

00:16:44.180 --> 00:16:44.980 align:middle line:10%
I just got here.

00:16:44.980 --> 00:16:46.760 align:middle line:90%
That's habit.

00:16:46.760 --> 00:16:48.500 align:middle line:84%
But when you do it
ritualistically,

00:16:48.500 --> 00:16:51.590 align:middle line:84%
it actually has a very
powerful effect on your health.

00:16:51.590 --> 00:16:53.810 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Wasn't that an old remedy?

00:16:53.810 --> 00:16:56.686 align:middle line:84%
An old cold remedy
is a shot of rum.

00:16:56.686 --> 00:16:57.560 align:middle line:90%
She's still using it.

00:16:57.560 --> 00:16:58.518 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: That's right.

00:16:58.518 --> 00:17:00.500 align:middle line:84%
And they'll say for
medicinal purposes only.

00:17:00.500 --> 00:17:01.300 align:middle line:90%
They'll say, but--

00:17:01.300 --> 00:17:02.750 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Right, right.

00:17:02.750 --> 00:17:07.280 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now, this next picture
is this wonderful couple.

00:17:07.280 --> 00:17:08.780 align:middle line:10%
They look great.

00:17:08.780 --> 00:17:10.170 align:middle line:10%
Who are these guys?

00:17:10.170 --> 00:17:12.589 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: They're what I
call the commitments to

00:17:12.589 --> 00:17:14.569 align:middle line:10%
for centering consciousness.

00:17:14.569 --> 00:17:17.240 align:middle line:10%
The present is never too
late to make commitments.

00:17:17.240 --> 00:17:19.099 align:middle line:10%
The one on the left,
they're married.

00:17:19.099 --> 00:17:20.540 align:middle line:10%
They got married.

00:17:20.540 --> 00:17:23.180 align:middle line:10%
And on the one on the
right, I think in his 90s,

00:17:23.180 --> 00:17:25.400 align:middle line:10%
he went back to college
and got his degree

00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:27.800 align:middle line:10%
when he was very
close to being 100.

00:17:27.800 --> 00:17:30.810 align:middle line:84%
So the present is never too
late to make commitments.

00:17:30.810 --> 00:17:31.610 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Wow.

00:17:31.610 --> 00:17:33.170 align:middle line:10%
And they got married at 100.

00:17:33.170 --> 00:17:36.110 align:middle line:10%
So there's centenarians that
are a hundred years old.

00:17:36.110 --> 00:17:37.850 align:middle line:84%
And then there's
super centenarians

00:17:37.850 --> 00:17:39.000 align:middle line:90%
that are a hundred--

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.280 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: 110.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:41.490 align:middle line:90%
LISA: 110.

00:17:41.490 --> 00:17:42.710 align:middle line:10%
Have you interviewed them?

00:17:42.710 --> 00:17:43.520 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: One, yes.

00:17:43.520 --> 00:17:45.050 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Where did he live?

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:46.620 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: This is in Ecuador.

00:17:46.620 --> 00:17:52.010 align:middle line:10%
And it's interesting.

00:17:52.010 --> 00:17:54.580 align:middle line:10%
I have the field
notes and I said,

00:17:54.580 --> 00:17:57.326 align:middle line:10%
so do you know you're
a super centenarian?

00:17:57.326 --> 00:17:59.450 align:middle line:84%
And he looks at me and
says, what the hell is that?

00:17:59.450 --> 00:18:01.490 align:middle line:84%
I said, well, you
know, you're over 110.

00:18:01.490 --> 00:18:03.470 align:middle line:90%
And it was very funny.

00:18:03.470 --> 00:18:05.780 align:middle line:84%
And what happens is
that these people

00:18:05.780 --> 00:18:10.640 align:middle line:84%
when they hit 100, the
deteriorating rate goes down.

00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:11.510 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Really?

00:18:11.510 --> 00:18:13.290 align:middle line:90%
They deteriorate less.

00:18:13.290 --> 00:18:14.090 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Less.

00:18:14.090 --> 00:18:16.200 align:middle line:90%
The deteriorate slower.

00:18:16.200 --> 00:18:20.450 align:middle line:84%
And, for example, a
90-year-old, healthy 90-year-old

00:18:20.450 --> 00:18:23.420 align:middle line:84%
has a greater probability
of staying healthier

00:18:23.420 --> 00:18:24.750 align:middle line:90%
than a 60-year-old.

00:18:24.750 --> 00:18:27.530 align:middle line:10%
They have more
experience with health.

00:18:27.530 --> 00:18:29.630 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Is that in that
particular culture?

00:18:29.630 --> 00:18:29.930 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: No, no.

00:18:29.930 --> 00:18:31.805 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Because out here,
we'll say, oh, at 90,

00:18:31.805 --> 00:18:33.800 align:middle line:10%
they lived a long, good life.

00:18:33.800 --> 00:18:36.240 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: But you see, the
centenarians in this country,

00:18:36.240 --> 00:18:38.120 align:middle line:10%
there are 100,000
centenarians now.

00:18:38.120 --> 00:18:39.020 align:middle line:10%
LISA: 100,000?

00:18:39.020 --> 00:18:40.310 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: They're the
fastest growing segment

00:18:40.310 --> 00:18:41.380 align:middle line:10%
of population in the US.

00:18:41.380 --> 00:18:42.320 align:middle line:90%
LISA: The US?

00:18:42.320 --> 00:18:43.400 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: And when you
ask the centenarians,

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:44.240 align:middle line:90%
they have a culture--

00:18:44.240 --> 00:18:44.480 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Really?

00:18:44.480 --> 00:18:45.938 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: Yes, they
have a culture.

00:18:45.938 --> 00:18:47.510 align:middle line:90%
They don't buy into that--

00:18:47.510 --> 00:18:50.530 align:middle line:84%
and unfortunately, medicine,
you go to a doctor, and not all,

00:18:50.530 --> 00:18:52.280 align:middle line:84%
but some will say,
well, what do you want?

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:53.330 align:middle line:90%
You're 90.

00:18:53.330 --> 00:18:55.039 align:middle line:84%
And there's this
doctor who is 80.

00:18:55.039 --> 00:18:57.080 align:middle line:84%
And I always tell this
story, because it's great.

00:18:57.080 --> 00:19:00.050 align:middle line:84%
It tells you how
we shape people.

00:19:00.050 --> 00:19:02.300 align:middle line:84%
His right knee was
hurting, and he was 80.

00:19:02.300 --> 00:19:03.757 align:middle line:90%
And he goes to a colleague.

00:19:03.757 --> 00:19:05.340 align:middle line:84%
And he said, my right
knee is hurting.

00:19:05.340 --> 00:19:05.900 align:middle line:90%
What do you want?

00:19:05.900 --> 00:19:06.590 align:middle line:90%
Your 80.

00:19:06.590 --> 00:19:08.215 align:middle line:84%
And he said, I'll
tell you what I want.

00:19:08.215 --> 00:19:09.500 align:middle line:10%
My left me is 80.

00:19:09.500 --> 00:19:10.400 align:middle line:90%
And it's not hurting.

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:13.700 align:middle line:84%
I want it to be
like my left knee.

00:19:13.700 --> 00:19:16.730 align:middle line:84%
But the attribution is
that, well, you're 90.

00:19:16.730 --> 00:19:18.974 align:middle line:84%
It's like saying,
just give up and die,

00:19:18.974 --> 00:19:20.140 align:middle line:90%
you've been around too long.

00:19:20.140 --> 00:19:22.460 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Well, what would you
say that these centenarians

00:19:22.460 --> 00:19:24.164 align:middle line:10%
have in common?

00:19:24.164 --> 00:19:26.330 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: These things that
we're pointing out here,

00:19:26.330 --> 00:19:29.090 align:middle line:10%
they have tremendous
sense of humor.

00:19:29.090 --> 00:19:32.180 align:middle line:84%
The present is always an
opportunity to make decisions.

00:19:32.180 --> 00:19:33.710 align:middle line:10%
They know how to forgive--

00:19:33.710 --> 00:19:35.340 align:middle line:10%
extremely important.

00:19:35.340 --> 00:19:37.520 align:middle line:10%
I interviewed one
here in the US who had

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:39.980 align:middle line:10%
been in a concentration camp.

00:19:39.980 --> 00:19:41.360 align:middle line:10%
They're not Pollyanna.

00:19:41.360 --> 00:19:43.880 align:middle line:10%
They not touchy feely.

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:45.890 align:middle line:10%
They're people that
go through the pain,

00:19:45.890 --> 00:19:47.390 align:middle line:10%
but then they get
out of their pain.

00:19:47.390 --> 00:19:48.800 align:middle line:90%
So I asked him, how was it?

00:19:48.800 --> 00:19:51.240 align:middle line:84%
He said, it was the worst
experience of my life.

00:19:51.240 --> 00:19:52.970 align:middle line:84%
And what do you
remember the most?

00:19:52.970 --> 00:19:57.440 align:middle line:84%
There was a kid my age,
who was a Nazi, army,

00:19:57.440 --> 00:20:00.180 align:middle line:84%
he would sneak
bread into my cell.

00:20:00.180 --> 00:20:01.334 align:middle line:90%
And that's what I remember.

00:20:01.334 --> 00:20:02.750 align:middle line:10%
I also remember
that my mother was

00:20:02.750 --> 00:20:05.316 align:middle line:10%
going to be very upset because
I couldn't write to her.

00:20:05.316 --> 00:20:06.409 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Oh, my goodness.

00:20:06.409 --> 00:20:08.450 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: And I said, so
what was the first thing

00:20:08.450 --> 00:20:09.940 align:middle line:10%
you did when you got out?

00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:12.290 align:middle line:10%
I talked to my mother and
I told her what happened,

00:20:12.290 --> 00:20:15.080 align:middle line:10%
and she got very
upset with the guards.

00:20:15.080 --> 00:20:18.440 align:middle line:84%
It's that resilience, that
way of looking at things.

00:20:18.440 --> 00:20:22.220 align:middle line:10%
And I asked him, do
you hate those people?

00:20:22.220 --> 00:20:23.959 align:middle line:10%
I dislike him, but
I'm not going to waste

00:20:23.959 --> 00:20:25.250 align:middle line:10%
any time with people like that.

00:20:25.250 --> 00:20:26.890 align:middle line:10%
I had too many things to do.

00:20:26.890 --> 00:20:27.860 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Wow.

00:20:27.860 --> 00:20:29.150 align:middle line:10%
Total appreciation for life.

00:20:29.150 --> 00:20:30.358 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Total appreciation.

00:20:30.358 --> 00:20:32.420 align:middle line:10%
And what he
remembered was an act

00:20:32.420 --> 00:20:37.730 align:middle line:10%
of kindness in a
puddle of infamy.

00:20:37.730 --> 00:20:40.670 align:middle line:10%
LISA: One act of kindness pulled
him through all of those years.

00:20:40.670 --> 00:20:41.503 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: That's it.

00:20:41.503 --> 00:20:42.910 align:middle line:10%
And that's all we need.

00:20:42.910 --> 00:20:44.660 align:middle line:10%
When I work with
patients and they tell me

00:20:44.660 --> 00:20:46.520 align:middle line:10%
they had a hard
life, I say, look,

00:20:46.520 --> 00:20:50.270 align:middle line:10%
it couldn't be worse than
a Nazi concentration camp.

00:20:50.270 --> 00:20:52.730 align:middle line:10%
Tune into what has
happened to you,

00:20:52.730 --> 00:20:54.710 align:middle line:10%
humane, something
that has touched you,

00:20:54.710 --> 00:20:56.420 align:middle line:10%
somebody that gave
you compassion.

00:20:56.420 --> 00:20:58.340 align:middle line:10%
And then build from there.

00:20:58.340 --> 00:21:00.110 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Do you live
your life differently

00:21:00.110 --> 00:21:02.000 align:middle line:10%
after interviewing all
these centenarians?

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:02.800 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:21:02.800 --> 00:21:05.930 align:middle line:10%
I don't tell my age anymore,
because they'll peg you.

00:21:05.930 --> 00:21:08.360 align:middle line:10%
You ask him, how old are you?

00:21:08.360 --> 00:21:11.840 align:middle line:10%
When I turned 100,
I start lying.

00:21:11.840 --> 00:21:14.090 align:middle line:84%
So if they're 100,
they'll say I'm 120.

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:15.800 align:middle line:84%
But before that, you
don't tell you age.

00:21:15.800 --> 00:21:17.280 align:middle line:90%
LISA: How funny.

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:20.630 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: And the reason,
I think, bioculturally

00:21:20.630 --> 00:21:24.350 align:middle line:10%
is that when you tell
your age, you're pegged.

00:21:24.350 --> 00:21:29.810 align:middle line:84%
If you say, I'm 80, oh,
OK, you look so good.

00:21:29.810 --> 00:21:31.964 align:middle line:84%
And they put you
into that mindset.

00:21:31.964 --> 00:21:34.130 align:middle line:84%
And they don't look what
you have done in your life.

00:21:34.130 --> 00:21:36.930 align:middle line:84%
They look at how long
you've been in life.

00:21:36.930 --> 00:21:38.220 align:middle line:90%
And they start treating you--

00:21:38.220 --> 00:21:39.020 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Definitely--

00:21:39.020 --> 00:21:39.936 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Differently.

00:21:39.936 --> 00:21:42.130 align:middle line:10%
And that's what ages people.

00:21:42.130 --> 00:21:44.580 align:middle line:84%
LISA: OK, so don't
tell your age,

00:21:44.580 --> 00:21:45.830 align:middle line:90%
is the one tip you've learned.

00:21:45.830 --> 00:21:46.880 align:middle line:90%
What's another one?

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:48.020 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Sense of humor.

00:21:48.020 --> 00:21:50.180 align:middle line:10%
Find humor in things.

00:21:50.180 --> 00:21:51.920 align:middle line:10%
Don't be pollyannish
in the sense

00:21:51.920 --> 00:21:55.220 align:middle line:10%
that if something bad happens,
you say, oh, I'm so happy.

00:21:55.220 --> 00:21:57.620 align:middle line:10%
Embody what's going
on and then let it go.

00:21:57.620 --> 00:22:01.340 align:middle line:10%
And then move into what
is the wisdom here?

00:22:01.340 --> 00:22:05.500 align:middle line:10%
The universe has
a lot of comedy.

00:22:05.500 --> 00:22:07.550 align:middle line:10%
Go into the comedy to
find out what happens.

00:22:07.550 --> 00:22:10.280 align:middle line:84%
Because what it does is
when you're laughing,

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:13.270 align:middle line:84%
you have cardiovascular
dilation.

00:22:13.270 --> 00:22:15.157 align:middle line:84%
You're increasing
immune function.

00:22:15.157 --> 00:22:16.740 align:middle line:10%
All kinds of things
that are going on.

00:22:16.740 --> 00:22:21.290 align:middle line:10%
But you can't do it
before you feel the hit.

00:22:21.290 --> 00:22:22.450 align:middle line:10%
You got to feel the hit.

00:22:22.450 --> 00:22:23.450 align:middle line:90%
You've got to embody it.

00:22:23.450 --> 00:22:25.769 align:middle line:84%
And then allow yourself
to experience it.

00:22:25.769 --> 00:22:26.810 align:middle line:90%
LISA: That's interesting.

00:22:26.810 --> 00:22:28.460 align:middle line:90%
I have a 10-year-old.

00:22:28.460 --> 00:22:30.590 align:middle line:90%
And we were at her soccer game.

00:22:30.590 --> 00:22:36.250 align:middle line:84%
And some of the other parents
get so upset with their kids.

00:22:36.250 --> 00:22:38.150 align:middle line:90%
They're 10.

00:22:38.150 --> 00:22:40.220 align:middle line:10%
And so something
happened on the field,

00:22:40.220 --> 00:22:42.584 align:middle line:10%
and I was in the background
next to the parents.

00:22:42.584 --> 00:22:44.750 align:middle line:10%
And I said, wow, that's
just pure comedy, because it

00:22:44.750 --> 00:22:47.060 align:middle line:10%
was a giant kerfuffle.

00:22:47.060 --> 00:22:51.020 align:middle line:84%
And one of the dads got so
mad, because he was just

00:22:51.020 --> 00:22:52.850 align:middle line:90%
taking it way too seriously.

00:22:52.850 --> 00:22:54.560 align:middle line:90%
He homeschools his kid.

00:22:54.560 --> 00:22:55.640 align:middle line:90%
This is her life.

00:22:55.640 --> 00:22:57.170 align:middle line:90%
And she's 10.

00:22:57.170 --> 00:23:00.170 align:middle line:84%
And so sometimes the
sense of humor gets lost

00:23:00.170 --> 00:23:02.682 align:middle line:84%
and it's being taught
to our kids these days.

00:23:02.682 --> 00:23:05.140 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: And if you're too
mechanical about teaching, then

00:23:05.140 --> 00:23:07.132 align:middle line:10%
what you're teaching
is to be mechanical.

00:23:07.132 --> 00:23:08.840 align:middle line:10%
Not the information
that you're teaching.

00:23:08.840 --> 00:23:09.840 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Yeah, yeah.

00:23:09.840 --> 00:23:13.220 align:middle line:84%
So how can the mind
wound the body?

00:23:13.220 --> 00:23:15.650 align:middle line:84%
How can it actually
work against us?

00:23:15.650 --> 00:23:18.230 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: If, for
example, we know

00:23:18.230 --> 00:23:20.270 align:middle line:10%
that there's
spontaneous healings,

00:23:20.270 --> 00:23:23.340 align:middle line:10%
a person believes
something and they actually

00:23:23.340 --> 00:23:25.520 align:middle line:10%
are allowed to heal themselves.

00:23:25.520 --> 00:23:27.630 align:middle line:10%
I'll give you an example.

00:23:27.630 --> 00:23:31.190 align:middle line:10%
There was reported in one
of psychiatric journals,

00:23:31.190 --> 00:23:33.560 align:middle line:10%
in a Catholic
hospital, the priest

00:23:33.560 --> 00:23:35.586 align:middle line:10%
came into the room
for this patient

00:23:35.586 --> 00:23:36.710 align:middle line:10%
to give him the last rites.

00:23:36.710 --> 00:23:37.834 align:middle line:10%
He gave him the last rites.

00:23:37.834 --> 00:23:39.530 align:middle line:10%
And he died in 15 minutes.

00:23:39.530 --> 00:23:42.800 align:middle line:10%
The problem is that he
went to the wrong room.

00:23:42.800 --> 00:23:46.010 align:middle line:10%
So what happened is that
in this person's mind,

00:23:46.010 --> 00:23:50.270 align:middle line:10%
two authorities in a context,
a doctor and a priest,

00:23:50.270 --> 00:23:53.480 align:middle line:10%
are telling me that I'm not
going to be around anymore.

00:23:53.480 --> 00:23:55.290 align:middle line:90%
They have that nocebo effect.

00:23:55.290 --> 00:23:56.780 align:middle line:84%
And when you do an
autopsy, there's

00:23:56.780 --> 00:24:00.380 align:middle line:84%
nothing wrong except some kind
of parasympathetic stopping

00:24:00.380 --> 00:24:01.730 align:middle line:90%
of the heart.

00:24:01.730 --> 00:24:05.030 align:middle line:84%
But now the person who
was scheduled to die

00:24:05.030 --> 00:24:09.410 align:middle line:84%
waited two days for the
priest to come before he died.

00:24:09.410 --> 00:24:12.980 align:middle line:84%
So the mind can wound and
can heal based on the belief

00:24:12.980 --> 00:24:14.270 align:middle line:90%
systems that we have.

00:24:14.270 --> 00:24:15.070 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Wow.

00:24:15.070 --> 00:24:16.640 align:middle line:10%
So you can really change--

00:24:16.640 --> 00:24:20.300 align:middle line:10%
I mean, the power of
changing your belief system.

00:24:20.300 --> 00:24:23.640 align:middle line:84%
And you said to me, look
for the signals of health.

00:24:23.640 --> 00:24:24.440 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:24:24.440 --> 00:24:26.360 align:middle line:84%
LISA: Not for the
signals of sickness.

00:24:26.360 --> 00:24:27.260 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Exactly.

00:24:27.260 --> 00:24:29.880 align:middle line:84%
And an example of what we
were talking about earlier,

00:24:29.880 --> 00:24:31.680 align:middle line:84%
if you're not feeling
well, for example--

00:24:31.680 --> 00:24:32.850 align:middle line:84%
and of course, you
have to check it out.

00:24:32.850 --> 00:24:33.680 align:middle line:90%
You have to go to your doctor.

00:24:33.680 --> 00:24:34.846 align:middle line:90%
But you're not feeling well.

00:24:34.846 --> 00:24:37.910 align:middle line:84%
You know there's an infection
or something or a cold.

00:24:37.910 --> 00:24:39.470 align:middle line:10%
Your body is going
to go into what's

00:24:39.470 --> 00:24:42.410 align:middle line:10%
called a sick response,
which is it'll slow down.

00:24:42.410 --> 00:24:46.160 align:middle line:10%
And you'll feel a little
bit groggy and tired.

00:24:46.160 --> 00:24:50.990 align:middle line:84%
Your system is saying, slow
down so I can take care of you.

00:24:50.990 --> 00:24:54.590 align:middle line:10%
So one way to begin to
help that is to tune

00:24:54.590 --> 00:24:57.260 align:middle line:10%
into any little signal
you have of recovery.

00:24:57.260 --> 00:25:00.560 align:middle line:10%
Like you're breathing a little
bit, you breathe into it.

00:25:00.560 --> 00:25:04.070 align:middle line:10%
You feel that less pain,
you tune into that.

00:25:04.070 --> 00:25:07.040 align:middle line:10%
So what you're doing is you're
kicking in signals of health

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:10.706 align:middle line:10%
rather signals of the
sickness response.

00:25:10.706 --> 00:25:12.080 align:middle line:10%
You compress the
time that you're

00:25:12.080 --> 00:25:14.150 align:middle line:10%
going to be spending
sick, but you're actually

00:25:14.150 --> 00:25:15.699 align:middle line:10%
helping your immune system.

00:25:15.699 --> 00:25:16.740 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Oh, I've done that.

00:25:16.740 --> 00:25:18.840 align:middle line:90%
Sat in bed miserable.

00:25:18.840 --> 00:25:20.270 align:middle line:90%
Felt sorry for myself.

00:25:20.270 --> 00:25:22.740 align:middle line:90%
Thought I was going to die.

00:25:22.740 --> 00:25:25.140 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, that's right, the
brain goes immediately

00:25:25.140 --> 00:25:26.791 align:middle line:90%
towards the signals of sickness.

00:25:26.791 --> 00:25:27.790 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: It defeats it.

00:25:27.790 --> 00:25:33.510 align:middle line:10%
And I was telling you before
the show that I flew about 22,

00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:37.430 align:middle line:10%
24 hours from Uruguay to
Miami, Miami to San Francisco.

00:25:37.430 --> 00:25:41.460 align:middle line:10%
Well, I was beginning to have
the kind of a sense of you're

00:25:41.460 --> 00:25:43.560 align:middle line:10%
going to catch something.

00:25:43.560 --> 00:25:45.630 align:middle line:84%
So I said, OK, what
happens is you're not

00:25:45.630 --> 00:25:48.180 align:middle line:84%
sleeping well on the
plane and not eating well.

00:25:48.180 --> 00:25:51.160 align:middle line:10%
And you're really getting
some immune deficiency.

