When my kids were very
young, I would take them out.

00:33:55.700 --> 00:33:57.074 align:middle line:10%
And I would tell
you, we're going

00:33:57.074 --> 00:33:58.662 align:middle line:10%
to find uncertainty today.

00:33:58.662 --> 00:33:59.870 align:middle line:10%
And we'd go out and get lost.

00:33:59.870 --> 00:34:00.290 align:middle line:10%
Where do we go?

00:34:00.290 --> 00:34:01.670 align:middle line:10%
Right, left, right, left.

00:34:01.670 --> 00:34:03.410 align:middle line:10%
And when we were
lost, OK, now let's

00:34:03.410 --> 00:34:05.480 align:middle line:10%
let chaos tell us
what we need to do.

00:34:05.480 --> 00:34:08.730 align:middle line:10%
And we'd start discovering
new restaurants, playgrounds.

00:34:08.730 --> 00:34:09.530 align:middle line:10%
LISA: How nice.

00:34:09.530 --> 00:34:10.946 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: But
indirectly what they

00:34:10.946 --> 00:34:13.340 align:middle line:10%
were learning is that
uncertainty is something

00:34:13.340 --> 00:34:14.989 align:middle line:10%
that gives you an opportunity
to learn, rather than to be

00:34:14.989 --> 00:34:15.620 align:middle line:10%
afraid.

00:34:15.620 --> 00:34:16.448 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Interesting.

00:34:16.448 --> 00:34:17.489 align:middle line:10%
That's a fun thing to do.

00:34:17.489 --> 00:34:19.230 align:middle line:10%
Now you live permanently in--

00:34:19.230 --> 00:34:20.030 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Uruguay.

00:34:20.030 --> 00:34:20.830 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Right now.

00:34:20.830 --> 00:34:21.800 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:34:21.800 --> 00:34:24.317 align:middle line:10%
And I travel quite a
bit with the work I do.

00:34:24.317 --> 00:34:25.400 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Where were you born?

00:34:25.400 --> 00:34:26.510 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: I was born
in Cuba actually.

00:34:26.510 --> 00:34:27.854 align:middle line:10%
And my father was from Spain.

00:34:27.854 --> 00:34:28.770 align:middle line:10%
My mother's from Cuba.

00:34:28.770 --> 00:34:31.484 align:middle line:10%
And I lived in the US most of
my life, in New York and Miami.

00:34:31.484 --> 00:34:33.650 align:middle line:10%
LISA: At what point did you
start studying medicine?

00:34:33.650 --> 00:34:35.022 align:middle line:10%
And why did you?

00:34:35.022 --> 00:34:36.980 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: I went from
medicine into psychology.

00:34:36.980 --> 00:34:38.765 align:middle line:10%
I moved into
neuropsychology, which

00:34:38.765 --> 00:34:41.480 align:middle line:10%
was something like
neurology and psychology,

00:34:41.480 --> 00:34:45.290 align:middle line:10%
because I was very interested
in really finding out

00:34:45.290 --> 00:34:46.250 align:middle line:10%
how the brain works.

00:34:46.250 --> 00:34:47.750 align:middle line:10%
And unfortunately,
when you study--

00:34:47.750 --> 00:34:49.300 align:middle line:10%
neuropsychologist
is changing stuff--

00:34:49.300 --> 00:34:50.716 align:middle line:10%
but when you study
neuropsychology

00:34:50.716 --> 00:34:52.760 align:middle line:10%
it studies the sick brain.

00:34:52.760 --> 00:34:54.080 align:middle line:10%
Somebody has a stroke.

00:34:54.080 --> 00:34:57.860 align:middle line:10%
And you have some damage
and broke an area,

00:34:57.860 --> 00:35:00.390 align:middle line:10%
then you're going to
have a type of aphasia.

00:35:00.390 --> 00:35:03.470 align:middle line:10%
But now Richard Davis
and other neuroscientists

00:35:03.470 --> 00:35:05.420 align:middle line:10%
are studying the healthy brain.

00:35:05.420 --> 00:35:07.670 align:middle line:10%
And what we know is that
the brain is not bipolar,

00:35:07.670 --> 00:35:08.470 align:middle line:10%
on and off.

00:35:08.470 --> 00:35:10.340 align:middle line:10%
The brain has a range.

00:35:10.340 --> 00:35:13.414 align:middle line:10%
If you lose some
ability for speech,

00:35:13.414 --> 00:35:14.830 align:middle line:10%
you can pick it
up somewhere else.

00:35:14.830 --> 00:35:18.990 align:middle line:10%
There is tremendous plasticity,
tremendous redundancy.

00:35:18.990 --> 00:35:21.957 align:middle line:10%
And so it has an opportunity
to repair itself.

00:35:21.957 --> 00:35:23.290 align:middle line:90%
LISA: How do you do that though?

00:35:23.290 --> 00:35:24.540 align:middle line:90%
How does it repair itself?

00:35:24.540 --> 00:35:26.380 align:middle line:84%
Do you know of a
specific technique?

00:35:26.380 --> 00:35:27.180 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:35:27.180 --> 00:35:29.430 align:middle line:84%
Well, let me give
you an example.

00:35:29.430 --> 00:35:33.120 align:middle line:10%
There was a scientist that
did some very interesting work

00:35:33.120 --> 00:35:37.540 align:middle line:10%
with teachers that were going
to teach blind students.

00:35:37.540 --> 00:35:40.470 align:middle line:10%
So in order for them to really
experience what it was like,

00:35:40.470 --> 00:35:41.820 align:middle line:10%
they were blinded.

00:35:41.820 --> 00:35:43.830 align:middle line:90%
They were covered for six weeks.

00:35:43.830 --> 00:35:44.870 align:middle line:90%
The teachers were.

00:35:44.870 --> 00:35:48.270 align:middle line:84%
And it takes about six weeks for
the brain to recontextualize.

00:35:48.270 --> 00:35:51.000 align:middle line:10%
And the occipital part of the
brain-- this part of back,

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:53.280 align:middle line:10%
it's a visual cortex--

00:35:53.280 --> 00:35:55.890 align:middle line:10%
when you are seeing
something, you have an MRI,

00:35:55.890 --> 00:35:59.520 align:middle line:10%
they show that part of
the brain lighting up.

00:35:59.520 --> 00:36:00.825 align:middle line:10%
And that's visual cortex.

00:36:00.825 --> 00:36:01.950 align:middle line:10%
And that's a visual cortex.

00:36:01.950 --> 00:36:03.180 align:middle line:10%
That's what it is.

00:36:03.180 --> 00:36:05.940 align:middle line:10%
These people were
blind for six weeks.

00:36:05.940 --> 00:36:07.110 align:middle line:10%
What happened to the brain?

00:36:07.110 --> 00:36:08.630 align:middle line:10%
It was no longer
the visual cortex.

00:36:08.630 --> 00:36:10.410 align:middle line:10%
It became tactile.

00:36:10.410 --> 00:36:13.080 align:middle line:84%
LISA: That was the center of
the brain that lit up the most?

00:36:13.080 --> 00:36:15.390 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: So instead
of being visual,

00:36:15.390 --> 00:36:19.440 align:middle line:84%
they became like the blind
people, and it became tactile.

00:36:19.440 --> 00:36:21.390 align:middle line:90%
So the brain can be so plastic.

00:36:21.390 --> 00:36:23.850 align:middle line:84%
Now, six weeks later,
after they started seeing,

00:36:23.850 --> 00:36:26.030 align:middle line:84%
it went back to occipital,
occipital visual.

00:36:26.030 --> 00:36:28.530 align:middle line:84%
LISA: So only in a matter of
six weeks the brain can change.

00:36:28.530 --> 00:36:29.910 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Can change, Yes.

00:36:29.910 --> 00:36:31.150 align:middle line:90%
LISA: That's fascinating.

00:36:31.150 --> 00:36:35.680 align:middle line:10%
When I went through a head
trauma about 13 years ago,

00:36:35.680 --> 00:36:37.410 align:middle line:10%
I lost my ability to speak.

00:36:37.410 --> 00:36:40.350 align:middle line:10%
And it took me a
while through EEG

00:36:40.350 --> 00:36:41.910 align:middle line:10%
and different types of things--

00:36:41.910 --> 00:36:42.868 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Biofeedback--

00:36:42.868 --> 00:36:46.250 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Yeah, biofeedback-- to
rebuild that part of my brain.

00:36:46.250 --> 00:36:47.050 align:middle line:10%
It's true.

00:36:47.050 --> 00:36:48.960 align:middle line:10%
I mean, look, I'm
speaking for a living now.

00:36:48.960 --> 00:36:50.100 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: And you're
speaking for a living.

00:36:50.100 --> 00:36:50.900 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:36:50.900 --> 00:36:54.460 align:middle line:84%
I used to have a phobia
of speaking in public.

00:36:54.460 --> 00:36:57.877 align:middle line:84%
In the fourth grade, I
had a five-minute speech.

00:36:57.877 --> 00:36:59.710 align:middle line:10%
And I looked at my
watch, I went, oh, God, I

00:36:59.710 --> 00:37:00.570 align:middle line:10%
got three minutes.

00:37:00.570 --> 00:37:02.492 align:middle line:10%
I'll never do public speaking.

00:37:02.492 --> 00:37:03.450 align:middle line:10%
And guess what happens?

00:37:03.450 --> 00:37:07.120 align:middle line:10%
You challenge yourself and
it becomes your passion.

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:07.920 align:middle line:10%
Like you.

00:37:07.920 --> 00:37:08.820 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Like you're doing.

00:37:08.820 --> 00:37:10.020 align:middle line:10%
All right, so let's
talk a little bit

00:37:10.020 --> 00:37:11.728 align:middle line:10%
about-- you mentioned
earlier in the show

00:37:11.728 --> 00:37:13.110 align:middle line:10%
about the stigmata people.

00:37:13.110 --> 00:37:15.485 align:middle line:10%
And I'm going to have you just
take a look really quickly

00:37:15.485 --> 00:37:16.485 align:middle line:10%
to see what stigmata is.

00:37:16.485 --> 00:37:18.068 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll talk
about these people

00:37:18.068 --> 00:37:19.260 align:middle line:90%
take a look at this video.

00:37:19.260 --> 00:37:20.520 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:37:20.520 --> 00:37:23.190 align:middle line:84%
NARRATOR: Clinical
psychologist Mario Martinez

00:37:23.190 --> 00:37:25.560 align:middle line:84%
has come to Mexico's
capital to investigate

00:37:25.560 --> 00:37:30.450 align:middle line:84%
one intriguing case, that
of 53-year-old grandmother

00:37:30.450 --> 00:37:32.340 align:middle line:90%
Elizabeth Sanchez.

00:37:32.340 --> 00:37:34.740 align:middle line:10%
At Easter and during
other holy days,

00:37:34.740 --> 00:37:39.450 align:middle line:10%
Elizabeth reportedly bleeds
from her hands, feet side, side,

00:37:39.450 --> 00:37:40.250 align:middle line:10%
and forehead.

00:37:40.250 --> 00:37:43.979 align:middle line:90%


00:37:43.979 --> 00:37:46.020 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: This is an
opportunity to really learn.

00:37:46.020 --> 00:37:47.640 align:middle line:84%
The way I look at it
is I'm a detective.

00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:48.780 align:middle line:84%
And I'm trying to
figure out what's

00:37:48.780 --> 00:37:49.810 align:middle line:90%
going on with the person.

00:37:49.810 --> 00:37:50.970 align:middle line:10%
And what's going on
with the evidence.

00:37:50.970 --> 00:37:52.230 align:middle line:90%
And I put them both together.

00:37:52.230 --> 00:37:54.270 align:middle line:84%
And it's fascinating
every time I do.

00:37:54.270 --> 00:37:58.250 align:middle line:10%
NARRATOR: The word stigmata
has evolved over the centuries.

00:37:58.250 --> 00:38:00.390 align:middle line:10%
It's Greek root,
stigma, literally

00:38:00.390 --> 00:38:02.910 align:middle line:10%
means mark, as in
the mark people

00:38:02.910 --> 00:38:05.790 align:middle line:10%
branded onto their cattle,
their slaves, and even

00:38:05.790 --> 00:38:07.650 align:middle line:10%
their soldiers.

00:38:07.650 --> 00:38:10.860 align:middle line:84%
The term appears just
once in the New Testament.

00:38:10.860 --> 00:38:14.660 align:middle line:10%
In his letter to the Galatians,
the Apostle Paul writes,

00:38:14.660 --> 00:38:17.729 align:middle line:10%
I bear the marks of the
Lord Jesus in my body.

00:38:17.729 --> 00:38:19.770 align:middle line:84%
MONSIGNOR CHARLES SCICLUNA:
Paul uses this title,

00:38:19.770 --> 00:38:23.700 align:middle line:84%
i am a servant or
slave of Christ.

00:38:23.700 --> 00:38:27.000 align:middle line:84%
For him, they are
marks of Christ,

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.880 align:middle line:84%
because they are the
result of his allegiance,

00:38:29.880 --> 00:38:32.270 align:middle line:90%
his loyalty to his master.

00:38:32.270 --> 00:38:35.560 align:middle line:90%


00:38:35.560 --> 00:38:38.470 align:middle line:84%
NARRATOR: It took more than
1,000 years for these stigmas

00:38:38.470 --> 00:38:43.090 align:middle line:84%
to become stigmata, the mystical
marks of Christ's crucifixion.

00:38:43.090 --> 00:38:48.560 align:middle line:90%


00:38:48.560 --> 00:38:51.920 align:middle line:84%
Martinez is one of only a
handful of medical experts

00:38:51.920 --> 00:38:54.470 align:middle line:90%
who specialize in stigmata.

00:38:54.470 --> 00:38:56.810 align:middle line:84%
He's been called on twice
by the Catholic church

00:38:56.810 --> 00:39:00.560 align:middle line:84%
to officially investigate the
authenticity of the phenomenon.

00:39:00.560 --> 00:39:02.870 align:middle line:84%
He's also looked into a
number of lower profile

00:39:02.870 --> 00:39:06.860 align:middle line:84%
cases on his own, two of which
he believes to be legitimate.

00:39:06.860 --> 00:39:09.362 align:middle line:90%


00:39:09.362 --> 00:39:10.820 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: An
authentic stigmatic is

00:39:10.820 --> 00:39:17.930 align:middle line:84%
one who has the wounds that can
not be explained biologically.

00:39:17.930 --> 00:39:21.680 align:middle line:84%
NARRATOR: This time Martinez
has a rare opportunity.

00:39:21.680 --> 00:39:23.030 align:middle line:90%
Elizabeth is bleeding.

00:39:23.030 --> 00:39:27.050 align:middle line:84%
And Martinez can take
a sample of his blood.

00:39:27.050 --> 00:39:29.030 align:middle line:84%
The cross on
Elizabeth's forehead

00:39:29.030 --> 00:39:31.850 align:middle line:84%
is not the typical
mark of a stigmatic.

00:39:31.850 --> 00:39:35.480 align:middle line:84%
It's not a wound that Jesus
received in his final hours.

00:39:35.480 --> 00:39:38.444 align:middle line:84%
But Martinez believes
it's just as interesting.

00:39:38.444 --> 00:39:39.860 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: There's
some things that

00:39:39.860 --> 00:39:42.920 align:middle line:10%
seem compatible with
what I seen before.

00:39:42.920 --> 00:39:44.570 align:middle line:10%
And there's some
very new things,

00:39:44.570 --> 00:39:45.860 align:middle line:10%
like the cross is very new.

00:39:45.860 --> 00:39:47.989 align:middle line:10%
The way that the blood
is dripping is very new.

00:39:47.989 --> 00:39:50.280 align:middle line:10%
I think that there's something
here that is legitimate.

00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:53.150 align:middle line:10%
It's worth looking into.

00:39:53.150 --> 00:39:55.310 align:middle line:10%
NARRATOR: Elizabeth
explains to Dr. Martinez

00:39:55.310 --> 00:39:57.900 align:middle line:10%
that she has received the
more familiar marks of Christ

00:39:57.900 --> 00:39:58.700 align:middle line:10%
in the past.

00:39:58.700 --> 00:39:59.240 align:middle line:90%
[PLAYBACK ENDS]

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:00.200 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Was that real?

00:40:00.200 --> 00:40:01.740 align:middle line:90%
Was that woman real?

00:40:01.740 --> 00:40:02.540 align:middle line:10%
Did she really--

00:40:02.540 --> 00:40:04.370 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Well, it seems like--

00:40:04.370 --> 00:40:07.282 align:middle line:10%
fortunately, all I have to do
is just to look at the science.

00:40:07.282 --> 00:40:08.990 align:middle line:10%
What we have to do is
we have to rule out

00:40:08.990 --> 00:40:11.690 align:middle line:10%
hysteria, multiple
personalities,

00:40:11.690 --> 00:40:15.050 align:middle line:10%
self-inflicted
injurious behavior.

00:40:15.050 --> 00:40:17.912 align:middle line:10%
And then we did bloodwork
to see what was going on.

00:40:17.912 --> 00:40:19.370 align:middle line:10%
And the bloodwork
showed that there

00:40:19.370 --> 00:40:23.510 align:middle line:10%
were deep wounds, which
means that you can't do that

00:40:23.510 --> 00:40:26.600 align:middle line:10%
without somebody noticing it.

00:40:26.600 --> 00:40:29.150 align:middle line:10%
She woke up one
evening, one night

00:40:29.150 --> 00:40:31.300 align:middle line:10%
in the middle of the night,
and she had the cross,

00:40:31.300 --> 00:40:32.480 align:middle line:10%
and screaming.

00:40:32.480 --> 00:40:34.390 align:middle line:84%
And her husband
looked at it-- and so

00:40:34.390 --> 00:40:36.920 align:middle line:84%
there were no knives or
nothing to cut herself.

00:40:36.920 --> 00:40:39.146 align:middle line:84%
LISA: So how did the blood
show it was a deep wound?

00:40:39.146 --> 00:40:40.520 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: There's
some blood work

00:40:40.520 --> 00:40:44.090 align:middle line:84%
that you can do to see if
it's superficial or deep

00:40:44.090 --> 00:40:45.830 align:middle line:90%
with the scab that they took.

00:40:45.830 --> 00:40:48.200 align:middle line:84%
But then they also did
immunological work.

00:40:48.200 --> 00:40:51.350 align:middle line:10%
And I was expecting her to
have a lot of neutrophils,

00:40:51.350 --> 00:40:53.900 align:middle line:10%
which are the ones that
fight infection, normal.

00:40:53.900 --> 00:40:57.312 align:middle line:10%
I was expecting cortisol to be
high because of stress, normal.

00:40:57.312 --> 00:40:58.770 align:middle line:10%
So all those things
were happening.

00:40:58.770 --> 00:40:59.810 align:middle line:90%
It wasn't healing.

00:40:59.810 --> 00:41:01.097 align:middle line:90%
It wasn't getting infected.

00:41:01.097 --> 00:41:02.930 align:middle line:84%
And the immune system
wasn't doing anything.

00:41:02.930 --> 00:41:04.030 align:middle line:84%
LISA: What type
of person was she?

00:41:04.030 --> 00:41:05.730 align:middle line:84%
I mean I understand
she was very religious.

00:41:05.730 --> 00:41:06.938 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: A spiritual person.

00:41:06.938 --> 00:41:09.920 align:middle line:10%
But another thing about it
is that kind of the fakes

00:41:09.920 --> 00:41:11.620 align:middle line:10%
like to capitalize on them.

00:41:11.620 --> 00:41:13.220 align:middle line:10%
They manipulate them.

00:41:13.220 --> 00:41:16.054 align:middle line:10%
For two years she was
hiding that she had that.

00:41:16.054 --> 00:41:17.720 align:middle line:84%
And people would come
to her would heal.

00:41:17.720 --> 00:41:18.830 align:middle line:90%
But she kept it secret.

00:41:18.830 --> 00:41:20.146 align:middle line:90%
She did want anybody to know.

00:41:20.146 --> 00:41:21.770 align:middle line:10%
But the interesting
thing here-- here's

00:41:21.770 --> 00:41:23.720 align:middle line:10%
the thing about it
that is so interesting.

00:41:23.720 --> 00:41:26.300 align:middle line:10%
I followed her for
years, several years.

00:41:26.300 --> 00:41:29.140 align:middle line:84%
And I helped her
get rid of the pain.

00:41:29.140 --> 00:41:30.280 align:middle line:90%
LISA: What pain?

00:41:30.280 --> 00:41:32.510 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: You feel like
that you've been crucified.

00:41:32.510 --> 00:41:35.010 align:middle line:84%
So it's like there's
a nail going in.

00:41:35.010 --> 00:41:37.910 align:middle line:84%
So I helped her get
rid of 80% of the pain

00:41:37.910 --> 00:41:41.000 align:middle line:84%
and then helped to
get rid of the stigma.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:44.090 align:middle line:10%
What happened was she was
no longer healing anybody.

00:41:44.090 --> 00:41:48.360 align:middle line:10%
People weren't seeing the pain
and the connection with Christ.

00:41:48.360 --> 00:41:49.160 align:middle line:10%
So what happened?

00:41:49.160 --> 00:41:50.780 align:middle line:10%
Stigmata came back.

00:41:50.780 --> 00:41:52.640 align:middle line:90%
So she said I'd rather have it.

00:41:52.640 --> 00:41:53.740 align:middle line:90%
I have much less pain.

00:41:53.740 --> 00:41:55.740 align:middle line:84%
I'd rather have it so
I can help people heal.

00:41:55.740 --> 00:41:56.540 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Really?

00:41:56.540 --> 00:41:58.164 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: But you
see, that's a culture

00:41:58.164 --> 00:42:01.340 align:middle line:10%
of suffering to reach Christ.

00:42:01.340 --> 00:42:02.850 align:middle line:84%
LISA: Well, let's
talk about that,

00:42:02.850 --> 00:42:06.500 align:middle line:84%
that abundance
versus deprivation.

00:42:06.500 --> 00:42:08.450 align:middle line:84%
You have a whole
concept on this.

00:42:08.450 --> 00:42:11.450 align:middle line:10%
What does that--

00:42:11.450 --> 00:42:13.880 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: There's a
valuation self-esteem

00:42:13.880 --> 00:42:17.540 align:middle line:10%
that tells us how much
we can accept graciously

00:42:17.540 --> 00:42:20.300 align:middle line:10%
without sabotaging
it or getting sick.

00:42:20.300 --> 00:42:22.790 align:middle line:10%
You see people that they
work all their lives

00:42:22.790 --> 00:42:27.380 align:middle line:10%
to have the mansion
somewhere and Brazil

00:42:27.380 --> 00:42:28.890 align:middle line:10%
and six weeks later, cancer.

00:42:28.890 --> 00:42:29.690 align:middle line:10%
It's too much.

00:42:29.690 --> 00:42:32.420 align:middle line:10%
Joy can be too dangerous
if their self-esteem is not

00:42:32.420 --> 00:42:34.490 align:middle line:10%
ready to handle that
level of abundance.

00:42:34.490 --> 00:42:38.780 align:middle line:10%
And the deprivation
mentality is that I'm not

00:42:38.780 --> 00:42:40.080 align:middle line:10%
able to reach that level.

00:42:40.080 --> 00:42:41.900 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to
have to look for--

00:42:41.900 --> 00:42:43.024 align:middle line:90%
I'll give an example.

00:42:43.024 --> 00:42:44.690 align:middle line:84%
Studies that were
done anthropologically

00:42:44.690 --> 00:42:47.840 align:middle line:84%
with people who came
from Cuba or came

00:42:47.840 --> 00:42:52.730 align:middle line:84%
from other countries, the ones
who had an abundance mentality,

00:42:52.730 --> 00:42:55.700 align:middle line:84%
they would move into
wealthy neighborhoods

00:42:55.700 --> 00:42:57.820 align:middle line:90%
in the most modest home.

00:42:57.820 --> 00:42:59.570 align:middle line:84%
The ones who had the
deprivation mentality

00:42:59.570 --> 00:43:01.184 align:middle line:84%
would go to the
ghettos immediately,

00:43:01.184 --> 00:43:02.600 align:middle line:84%
because that's all
they could see.

00:43:02.600 --> 00:43:05.030 align:middle line:90%
They can only see the worse.

00:43:05.030 --> 00:43:07.100 align:middle line:10%
And you interview
them 10 years later,

00:43:07.100 --> 00:43:10.880 align:middle line:10%
and they lived exactly the
expectations that they had.

00:43:10.880 --> 00:43:12.010 align:middle line:90%
You would ask them--

00:43:12.010 --> 00:43:14.080 align:middle line:84%
here's the disempowered
and empowered.

00:43:14.080 --> 00:43:16.416 align:middle line:84%
Disempowered-- well, I
don't speak the language.

00:43:16.416 --> 00:43:18.290 align:middle line:10%
You know, this is, yeah,
it's a great country

00:43:18.290 --> 00:43:19.580 align:middle line:10%
if you speak English.

00:43:19.580 --> 00:43:21.710 align:middle line:84%
So where are you going
to be 10 years from now?

00:43:21.710 --> 00:43:23.240 align:middle line:90%
The way I am now.

00:43:23.240 --> 00:43:25.640 align:middle line:10%
The other person, empowered--
a great opportunity

00:43:25.640 --> 00:43:26.882 align:middle line:10%
to learn English.

00:43:26.882 --> 00:43:28.340 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to find
out what I can do

00:43:28.340 --> 00:43:30.480 align:middle line:90%
in the country of opportunity.

00:43:30.480 --> 00:43:33.380 align:middle line:10%
10 years later,
abundance, deprivation.

00:43:33.380 --> 00:43:36.680 align:middle line:84%
Not only that, but illnesses,
and the other one healthy.

00:43:36.680 --> 00:43:37.540 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Really?

00:43:37.540 --> 00:43:38.855 align:middle line:10%
Illnesses were in
the deprivation?

00:43:38.855 --> 00:43:40.896 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: In the deprivation
because deprivation,

00:43:40.896 --> 00:43:42.740 align:middle line:84%
a deprivation of
health, of everything.

00:43:42.740 --> 00:43:46.280 align:middle line:10%
LISA: So back to the
stigmata really quickly,

00:43:46.280 --> 00:43:48.530 align:middle line:10%
you had a whole course
that you taught,

00:43:48.530 --> 00:43:50.464 align:middle line:10%
called from fibromyalgia--

00:43:50.464 --> 00:43:51.380 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: To stigmata.

00:43:51.380 --> 00:43:52.580 align:middle line:10%
LISA: To stigmata.

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:53.720 align:middle line:10%
What's the correlation.

00:43:53.720 --> 00:43:57.200 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: The
correlation is that they

00:43:57.200 --> 00:44:00.850 align:middle line:10%
both have a self-created-- one
because of religious views.

00:44:00.850 --> 00:44:01.750 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Oh, I see.

00:44:01.750 --> 00:44:04.333 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: And the other one is
because of the learning that we

00:44:04.333 --> 00:44:06.590 align:middle line:90%
talked, that you can learn to.

00:44:06.590 --> 00:44:09.530 align:middle line:10%
So one is very explicitly
showing, not an illness,

00:44:09.530 --> 00:44:13.470 align:middle line:10%
but an actual tearing of tissue.

00:44:13.470 --> 00:44:15.150 align:middle line:10%
And the other one
is more subtle,

00:44:15.150 --> 00:44:17.120 align:middle line:10%
but they have very
similar processes.

00:44:17.120 --> 00:44:18.590 align:middle line:10%
So the mind body code.

00:44:18.590 --> 00:44:22.697 align:middle line:10%
LISA: How did you discover all
of this and these connections?

00:44:22.697 --> 00:44:24.280 align:middle line:10%
This is not something
that you would--

00:44:24.280 --> 00:44:26.090 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: No, no, I was
really dissatisfied--

00:44:26.090 --> 00:44:26.540 align:middle line:10%
LISA: See in medicine--

00:44:26.540 --> 00:44:28.470 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: With
conventional science.

00:44:28.470 --> 00:44:30.307 align:middle line:90%
What I studied was dissatisfied.

00:44:30.307 --> 00:44:32.640 align:middle line:84%
And then I just had these
things, what I call the drift.

00:44:32.640 --> 00:44:34.820 align:middle line:10%
I was asked by the
Catholic church

00:44:34.820 --> 00:44:36.049 align:middle line:10%
to investigate this case.

00:44:36.049 --> 00:44:37.590 align:middle line:10%
And I didn't know
how they found out.

00:44:37.590 --> 00:44:40.880 align:middle line:84%
And they said the
Vatican has ways.

00:44:40.880 --> 00:44:41.960 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Wow.

00:44:41.960 --> 00:44:44.550 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: So they call, we know
you do psychoneuroimmunology.

00:44:44.550 --> 00:44:47.940 align:middle line:84%
We want you to investigate
this priest in the Caribbean

00:44:47.940 --> 00:44:49.820 align:middle line:90%
who had the stigmata.

00:44:49.820 --> 00:44:52.280 align:middle line:84%
Then you know BBC
picked up on it.

00:44:52.280 --> 00:44:53.720 align:middle line:84%
And anytime there's
any stigmatic,

00:44:53.720 --> 00:44:55.790 align:middle line:90%
they call me to investigate it.

00:44:55.790 --> 00:44:58.540 align:middle line:84%
LISA: You're now the foremost
stigmata investigator.

00:44:58.540 --> 00:44:59.990 align:middle line:10%
Yeah, that's great.

00:44:59.990 --> 00:45:03.740 align:middle line:10%
Now, you do talk about the
defiance of predatory science

00:45:03.740 --> 00:45:05.870 align:middle line:10%
and this is the side
that we have here.

00:45:05.870 --> 00:45:07.660 align:middle line:10%
What do you mean by that?

00:45:07.660 --> 00:45:09.410 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Predatory
science is the science

00:45:09.410 --> 00:45:15.800 align:middle line:10%
that actually tries to increase
the marketing of whatever they

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:17.930 align:middle line:10%
do for the illness.

00:45:17.930 --> 00:45:24.260 align:middle line:10%
For example, you have the
science that says, well,

00:45:24.260 --> 00:45:27.900 align:middle line:10%
it's no longer necessary to have
this prevention test done once

00:45:27.900 --> 00:45:28.700 align:middle line:10%
a year.

00:45:28.700 --> 00:45:30.830 align:middle line:10%
Now you have to do
it every six months.

00:45:30.830 --> 00:45:33.080 align:middle line:10%
And all of that work, all
of that preventive work,

00:45:33.080 --> 00:45:36.740 align:middle line:10%
we're 37th in the world
in longevity and health.

00:45:36.740 --> 00:45:39.000 align:middle line:10%
So obviously it doesn't work.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:41.910 align:middle line:10%
It doesn't work very well, but
people make a lot of money.

00:45:41.910 --> 00:45:44.290 align:middle line:10%
So what we do have is
we have a consciousness,

00:45:44.290 --> 00:45:46.550 align:middle line:10%
a palliative medicine
consciousness.

00:45:46.550 --> 00:45:49.760 align:middle line:10%
How can I make it easier for
you to go on with your illness?

00:45:49.760 --> 00:45:52.610 align:middle line:10%
Rather than, how can I heal you?

00:45:52.610 --> 00:45:57.390 align:middle line:10%
LISA: So in having those tests
and those checkups and breast

00:45:57.390 --> 00:45:59.450 align:middle line:10%
scans and heart scans
and things like that,

00:45:59.450 --> 00:46:01.610 align:middle line:10%
you think that it
actually causes people

00:46:01.610 --> 00:46:03.030 align:middle line:10%
to look for the illness more?

00:46:03.030 --> 00:46:03.830 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: More.

00:46:03.830 --> 00:46:08.270 align:middle line:10%
And I don't want to promote that
you shouldn't have checkups.

00:46:08.270 --> 00:46:09.440 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that's you're right.

00:46:09.440 --> 00:46:10.240 align:middle line:90%
I don't.

00:46:10.240 --> 00:46:11.330 align:middle line:90%
I don't.

00:46:11.330 --> 00:46:14.210 align:middle line:10%
Because what is the
job of the physician?

00:46:14.210 --> 00:46:16.020 align:middle line:10%
To find something
wrong with you.

00:46:16.020 --> 00:46:18.770 align:middle line:10%
And there are physicians
who are teachers.

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:21.650 align:middle line:10%
So rather than going there to
find something wrong with you,

00:46:21.650 --> 00:46:23.309 align:middle line:10%
they teach you how to prevent.

00:46:23.309 --> 00:46:25.100 align:middle line:10%
And they teach you how
to empower yourself.

00:46:25.100 --> 00:46:26.660 align:middle line:10%
LISA: And there's some that
are healers and are really

00:46:26.660 --> 00:46:27.620 align:middle line:10%
good healers.

00:46:27.620 --> 00:46:29.810 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: And you want to
go to a scientist rather

00:46:29.810 --> 00:46:31.070 align:middle line:10%
than a technician.

00:46:31.070 --> 00:46:34.520 align:middle line:10%
A scientist will say, OK, if you
can show me, if you can give me

00:46:34.520 --> 00:46:35.872 align:middle line:10%
evidence, I'll work with you.

00:46:35.872 --> 00:46:37.830 align:middle line:10%
The technician will say,
no, that doesn't work.

00:46:37.830 --> 00:46:38.420 align:middle line:10%
This is how it is.

00:46:38.420 --> 00:46:39.050 align:middle line:10%
I'm the doctor.

00:46:39.050 --> 00:46:39.410 align:middle line:10%
I know.

00:46:39.410 --> 00:46:40.220 align:middle line:10%
You don't know.

00:46:40.220 --> 00:46:41.940 align:middle line:84%
You take this and
don't question me.

00:46:41.940 --> 00:46:43.070 align:middle line:90%
That's the technician.

00:46:43.070 --> 00:46:45.227 align:middle line:84%
They only believe
what they can measure.

00:46:45.227 --> 00:46:47.060 align:middle line:84%
LISA: Which has been
statistically measured.

00:46:47.060 --> 00:46:47.420 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: That's right.

00:46:47.420 --> 00:46:48.836 align:middle line:84%
LISA: But every
body is different.

00:46:48.836 --> 00:46:51.680 align:middle line:84%
And that really does
get omitted a lot.

00:46:51.680 --> 00:46:52.480 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:46:52.480 --> 00:46:53.870 align:middle line:10%
And everything is contextual.

00:46:53.870 --> 00:46:56.400 align:middle line:84%
You might have high blood
pressure in one context

00:46:56.400 --> 00:46:57.200 align:middle line:90%
and not in another.

00:46:57.200 --> 00:46:59.720 align:middle line:10%
But if you're already
defined as a hypertensive,

00:46:59.720 --> 00:47:01.250 align:middle line:10%
then you're hypertensive
for the rest of your life.

00:47:01.250 --> 00:47:03.500 align:middle line:10%
You take medication that has
side effects or something

00:47:03.500 --> 00:47:04.590 align:middle line:10%
else and so forth.

00:47:04.590 --> 00:47:08.160 align:middle line:84%
And many of the hypertension can
be treated without medication--

00:47:08.160 --> 00:47:10.490 align:middle line:90%
diet, exercise, mindsets.

00:47:10.490 --> 00:47:13.510 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Well, let's talk about
the mindset of the immune system

00:47:13.510 --> 00:47:15.500 align:middle line:10%
because it is so intelligent.

00:47:15.500 --> 00:47:19.580 align:middle line:10%
And it just
automatically strives

00:47:19.580 --> 00:47:23.420 align:middle line:10%
towards homeostasis every
single second of the day.

00:47:23.420 --> 00:47:27.770 align:middle line:10%
How do you tap into that
intelligence to heal your body?

00:47:27.770 --> 00:47:30.440 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Well, the first
thing is to get out of the fear

00:47:30.440 --> 00:47:32.430 align:middle line:10%
that as you grow
older you deteriorate.

00:47:32.430 --> 00:47:34.679 align:middle line:10%
That's the first thing,
because you live in that fear.

00:47:34.679 --> 00:47:39.080 align:middle line:10%
And the next birthday, it's
almost like, oh, my God,

00:47:39.080 --> 00:47:40.702 align:middle line:10%
I'm such and such an age.

00:47:40.702 --> 00:47:41.660 align:middle line:10%
That's the first thing.

00:47:41.660 --> 00:47:43.730 align:middle line:10%
And the second, to
realize that a lot

00:47:43.730 --> 00:47:45.830 align:middle line:10%
of the processes
that are going on,

00:47:45.830 --> 00:47:49.020 align:middle line:10%
the body's fighting
pre-cancer cells constantly.

00:47:49.020 --> 00:47:50.810 align:middle line:10%
You don't even know about.

00:47:50.810 --> 00:47:54.370 align:middle line:10%
The body is repairing
tissue constantly.

00:47:54.370 --> 00:47:58.040 align:middle line:10%
The immune system is creating
antibodies for things

00:47:58.040 --> 00:47:59.570 align:middle line:10%
that it doesn't even know exist.

00:47:59.570 --> 00:48:04.250 align:middle line:10%
It has a kind of a epigenetic
value that creates in random.

00:48:04.250 --> 00:48:06.260 align:middle line:10%
So it has protection
for everything.

00:48:06.260 --> 00:48:09.050 align:middle line:10%
And then second is that you have
to have a philosophy of life.

00:48:09.050 --> 00:48:10.190 align:middle line:10%
What am I doing here?

00:48:10.190 --> 00:48:13.640 align:middle line:10%
Am I here to live and
die and then that's it?

00:48:13.640 --> 00:48:17.564 align:middle line:10%
Or am I here to learn, to
love, to have pleasure,

00:48:17.564 --> 00:48:18.980 align:middle line:10%
to enjoy the
pleasure that I have?

00:48:18.980 --> 00:48:22.430 align:middle line:84%
And that indirectly
causes health.

00:48:22.430 --> 00:48:23.360 align:middle line:90%
Indirectly.

00:48:23.360 --> 00:48:25.670 align:middle line:10%
LISA: So you're basically
teaching your mind

00:48:25.670 --> 00:48:27.147 align:middle line:10%
to act like the
immune system does.

00:48:27.147 --> 00:48:28.730 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Like the
immune system does.

00:48:28.730 --> 00:48:30.080 align:middle line:10%
Resilience.

00:48:30.080 --> 00:48:33.730 align:middle line:10%
Tremendous ability to
function under turbulence.

00:48:33.730 --> 00:48:35.270 align:middle line:10%
And tremendous resources.

00:48:35.270 --> 00:48:38.120 align:middle line:10%
But here's a real simple
way to look at it.

00:48:38.120 --> 00:48:41.390 align:middle line:84%
The immune system
basically has two modes.

00:48:41.390 --> 00:48:44.540 align:middle line:84%
It is either empowered
or it's helpless.

00:48:44.540 --> 00:48:48.110 align:middle line:10%
And it has two principles,
what I call empowerment

00:48:48.110 --> 00:48:49.460 align:middle line:10%
1 and empowerment 2.

00:48:49.460 --> 00:48:53.630 align:middle line:84%
Any cell, the cell will go--
a neutrophil, a macrophage,

00:48:53.630 --> 00:48:55.390 align:middle line:90%
whatever--

00:48:55.390 --> 00:48:57.070 align:middle line:90%
E1 I call it, empowerment 1.

00:48:57.070 --> 00:49:00.790 align:middle line:10%
What can I do for myself
that nobody could do for me?

00:49:00.790 --> 00:49:01.590 align:middle line:90%
That's it.

00:49:01.590 --> 00:49:02.964 align:middle line:84%
LISA: Give me an
example of that.

00:49:02.964 --> 00:49:05.780 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: OK, you're working and
instead of going to your boss,

00:49:05.780 --> 00:49:07.370 align:middle line:84%
you're going, what
can I do to take

00:49:07.370 --> 00:49:08.940 align:middle line:90%
care of what's going on here?

00:49:08.940 --> 00:49:09.740 align:middle line:90%
I'm sick.

00:49:09.740 --> 00:49:12.020 align:middle line:84%
What can I do to
take care of today?

00:49:12.020 --> 00:49:13.250 align:middle line:10%
How can I take that--

00:49:13.250 --> 00:49:16.100 align:middle line:10%
once you exhaust
that, you go to E2.

00:49:16.100 --> 00:49:18.830 align:middle line:10%
What can others do for me
that I can't do for myself?

00:49:18.830 --> 00:49:20.690 align:middle line:10%
And that's how the
immune system functions.

00:49:20.690 --> 00:49:24.350 align:middle line:10%
You have a cell that
tries to fight some kind

00:49:24.350 --> 00:49:26.930 align:middle line:10%
of microorganism or whatever.

00:49:26.930 --> 00:49:27.890 align:middle line:10%
And it fights it.

00:49:27.890 --> 00:49:29.560 align:middle line:10%
But then here's the
pre-cancer cell.

00:49:29.560 --> 00:49:31.340 align:middle line:10%
And it says, no, I
can't handle this.

00:49:31.340 --> 00:49:33.380 align:middle line:10%
Let me call in
the ones that can.

00:49:33.380 --> 00:49:35.390 align:middle line:10%
So E1 and E2.

00:49:35.390 --> 00:49:37.550 align:middle line:10%
That alone, if you
do that in your life,

00:49:37.550 --> 00:49:40.610 align:middle line:10%
you're using immune
function wisdom.

00:49:40.610 --> 00:49:43.250 align:middle line:10%
LISA: So have you seen
spontaneous remissions

00:49:43.250 --> 00:49:46.070 align:middle line:10%
in your life, in your
practice with people?

00:49:46.070 --> 00:49:49.280 align:middle line:10%
Have you seen them really
truly heal their bodies

00:49:49.280 --> 00:49:50.270 align:middle line:10%
with their mind?

00:49:50.270 --> 00:49:51.070 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:49:51.070 --> 00:49:54.360 align:middle line:10%
And it's rare, because we
still don't know the dynamics.

00:49:54.360 --> 00:49:55.160 align:middle line:10%
We're learning.

00:49:55.160 --> 00:49:59.090 align:middle line:10%
But this case in Mexico
City, the boy who

00:49:59.090 --> 00:50:02.330 align:middle line:10%
was cured of leukemia,
because just being

00:50:02.330 --> 00:50:04.250 align:middle line:10%
around the stigmatic,
and the man who

00:50:04.250 --> 00:50:06.830 align:middle line:10%
was cured of prostate
cancer, I checked

00:50:06.830 --> 00:50:09.740 align:middle line:10%
with their physician,
nine months later,

00:50:09.740 --> 00:50:13.645 align:middle line:10%
no symptoms, complete
remission, without any symptoms.

00:50:13.645 --> 00:50:15.020 align:middle line:10%
LISA: So do you
think that that's

00:50:15.020 --> 00:50:18.770 align:middle line:10%
their immune system matching the
immune system of the stigmatic?

00:50:18.770 --> 00:50:22.970 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: No, we have to
have permission to heal.

00:50:22.970 --> 00:50:26.990 align:middle line:10%
We have to get permission
from God, a doctor,

00:50:26.990 --> 00:50:31.580 align:middle line:10%
or from a shaman to trigger
what we already have.

00:50:31.580 --> 00:50:34.140 align:middle line:10%
Our healing system we already
have, it has to be triggered.

00:50:34.140 --> 00:50:35.460 align:middle line:10%
So we need permission.

00:50:35.460 --> 00:50:36.890 align:middle line:10%
And if this person
who's Catholic

00:50:36.890 --> 00:50:39.410 align:middle line:10%
believes that there's
divine intervention,

00:50:39.410 --> 00:50:42.250 align:middle line:10%
they're around a holy person,
that holy person can heal them.

00:50:42.250 --> 00:50:44.560 align:middle line:84%
And even a child,
he didn't even know.

00:50:44.560 --> 00:50:45.810 align:middle line:90%
It's a cultural belief system.

00:50:45.810 --> 00:50:48.020 align:middle line:84%
LISA: Couldn't we give that
permission to ourselves?

00:50:48.020 --> 00:50:49.160 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Yes, we can.

00:50:49.160 --> 00:50:51.830 align:middle line:84%
And that's when people but get
to levels where they actually

00:50:51.830 --> 00:50:53.220 align:middle line:90%
are very empowered.

00:50:53.220 --> 00:50:55.496 align:middle line:90%
And that's what centenarians do.

00:50:55.496 --> 00:50:56.620 align:middle line:90%
LISA: They heal themselves?

00:50:56.620 --> 00:50:58.078 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: Yes, they
go to a doctor.

00:50:58.078 --> 00:51:00.690 align:middle line:84%
And he says, well, you have
an illness that 99% of people

00:51:00.690 --> 00:51:01.490 align:middle line:90%
die from.

00:51:01.490 --> 00:51:03.656 align:middle line:84%
And he says, well, I'm going
to go out and celebrate

00:51:03.656 --> 00:51:05.309 align:middle line:90%
because I must be that 1%.

00:51:05.309 --> 00:51:06.350 align:middle line:90%
That's how they function.

00:51:06.350 --> 00:51:09.200 align:middle line:84%
Resilient and they
don't give up.

00:51:09.200 --> 00:51:11.600 align:middle line:84%
LISA: How many of them
have you interviewed?

00:51:11.600 --> 00:51:13.820 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Probably
about 400, 450.

00:51:13.820 --> 00:51:15.230 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Wow.

00:51:15.230 --> 00:51:17.180 align:middle line:90%
Oh, my goodness.

00:51:17.180 --> 00:51:19.520 align:middle line:84%
And what is the main thing
that you think that they

00:51:19.520 --> 00:51:20.900 align:middle line:90%
eat that keeps them healthy?

00:51:20.900 --> 00:51:22.317 align:middle line:84%
Do you think it's
the food at all?

00:51:22.317 --> 00:51:23.899 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: I used to
think it was food.

00:51:23.899 --> 00:51:24.800 align:middle line:90%
Some will eat meat.

00:51:24.800 --> 00:51:26.450 align:middle line:90%
Some are vegetarians.

00:51:26.450 --> 00:51:28.030 align:middle line:90%
Some eat fish.

00:51:28.030 --> 00:51:31.130 align:middle line:90%
Some, a lot of lactose.

00:51:31.130 --> 00:51:32.510 align:middle line:90%
So it's basically how they eat.

00:51:32.510 --> 00:51:34.060 align:middle line:10%
They don't abuse food.

00:51:34.060 --> 00:51:37.705 align:middle line:10%
There are some that are
hefty, but very few obese.

00:51:37.705 --> 00:51:40.450 align:middle line:10%


00:51:40.450 --> 00:51:42.830 align:middle line:10%
So they basically
enjoy what they eat.

00:51:42.830 --> 00:51:47.060 align:middle line:10%
They smoke, some, very
moderately, ritualistically.

00:51:47.060 --> 00:51:48.380 align:middle line:10%
They drink wine.

00:51:48.380 --> 00:51:50.690 align:middle line:10%
They'll have rum at
the end of the day.

00:51:50.690 --> 00:51:52.237 align:middle line:10%
But they don't abuse.

00:51:52.237 --> 00:51:53.320 align:middle line:90%
It's not an abuse of the--

00:51:53.320 --> 00:51:53.960 align:middle line:90%
LISA: It's ritualistic.

00:51:53.960 --> 00:51:54.830 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: It's ritualistic.

00:51:54.830 --> 00:51:56.750 align:middle line:84%
So it has a medicinal
purpose in the sense

00:51:56.750 --> 00:51:58.541 align:middle line:84%
that if I'm going to
have this as a ritual.

00:51:58.541 --> 00:52:02.450 align:middle line:84%
If you have one shot
of rum at night,

00:52:02.450 --> 00:52:05.420 align:middle line:84%
obviously it's not going to kill
you because this woman is 103.

00:52:05.420 --> 00:52:08.510 align:middle line:84%
So there's evidence there that
it's not going to kill you.

00:52:08.510 --> 00:52:10.190 align:middle line:90%
I'm not suggesting you do that.

00:52:10.190 --> 00:52:12.290 align:middle line:84%
I'm suggesting you
find a ritual that

00:52:12.290 --> 00:52:13.970 align:middle line:84%
has meaning in your
culture, whatever

00:52:13.970 --> 00:52:17.270 align:middle line:84%
that is, whether it's meditation
or prayer or whatever it is.

00:52:17.270 --> 00:52:18.270 align:middle line:90%
And you do it.

00:52:18.270 --> 00:52:20.390 align:middle line:90%
And that has the healing effect.

00:52:20.390 --> 00:52:22.342 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Have you ever been sick?

00:52:22.342 --> 00:52:24.050 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Yeah, I've
had colds and things

00:52:24.050 --> 00:52:27.110 align:middle line:10%
like that and one accident,
three broken ribs.

00:52:27.110 --> 00:52:30.050 align:middle line:84%
But I've never been
really sick in that sense.

00:52:30.050 --> 00:52:33.380 align:middle line:84%
LISA: If you were to
catch a virus or whatnot,

00:52:33.380 --> 00:52:37.220 align:middle line:84%
do you think that all that
you know you could actually

00:52:37.220 --> 00:52:38.355 align:middle line:90%
heal that with your mind?

00:52:38.355 --> 00:52:39.980 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: With your
mind and your body.

00:52:39.980 --> 00:52:43.790 align:middle line:10%
And if you can't, then you can
go to an understanding doctor,

00:52:43.790 --> 00:52:45.980 align:middle line:10%
to a scientist,
not a technician.

00:52:45.980 --> 00:52:49.070 align:middle line:10%
The scientist will say, if you
show me evidence, I'll agree.

00:52:49.070 --> 00:52:51.459 align:middle line:84%
A technician will say, no,
only what I can measure.

00:52:51.459 --> 00:52:53.000 align:middle line:84%
That's a technician,
not a scientist.

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:54.680 align:middle line:10%
LISA: I mean it's
interesting, because I

00:52:54.680 --> 00:52:59.450 align:middle line:10%
think that we need to empower
ourselves more when it comes

00:52:59.450 --> 00:53:01.940 align:middle line:10%
to health care these days
because our health care

00:53:01.940 --> 00:53:05.660 align:middle line:10%
system is changing so
quickly and so frequently.

00:53:05.660 --> 00:53:09.260 align:middle line:10%
That there's a situation
where we're in as a country

00:53:09.260 --> 00:53:12.840 align:middle line:10%
right now, we don't really
know the outcome of it.

00:53:12.840 --> 00:53:16.294 align:middle line:10%
So I mean, some doctors are
charging an arm and a leg

00:53:16.294 --> 00:53:17.960 align:middle line:10%
because they don't
want to go-- and they

00:53:17.960 --> 00:53:19.880 align:middle line:10%
want to privatize now
because they don't

00:53:19.880 --> 00:53:21.230 align:middle line:10%
want to go through Obamacare.

00:53:21.230 --> 00:53:23.530 align:middle line:10%
And there's so many
different things

00:53:23.530 --> 00:53:25.550 align:middle line:10%
that's happening with
our health care system.

00:53:25.550 --> 00:53:29.480 align:middle line:10%
Is there any way that you
know of that can actually

00:53:29.480 --> 00:53:35.390 align:middle line:10%
help train doctors to be
more of the intuitive healer

00:53:35.390 --> 00:53:37.490 align:middle line:10%
rather than just the technician?

00:53:37.490 --> 00:53:40.700 align:middle line:84%
Are they running so scared
at this point that that's

00:53:40.700 --> 00:53:41.750 align:middle line:90%
a thing of the past?

00:53:41.750 --> 00:53:42.791 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: We're doing it.

00:53:42.791 --> 00:53:45.050 align:middle line:84%
We've trained over 400 doctors
in different countries,

00:53:45.050 --> 00:53:48.236 align:middle line:84%
and in Uruguay and in Ireland
and the United States.

00:53:48.236 --> 00:53:49.735 align:middle line:10%
But there's some
medical schools now

00:53:49.735 --> 00:53:51.943 align:middle line:10%
that are doing integrative
medicine, who are actually

00:53:51.943 --> 00:53:53.029 align:middle line:10%
bringing in other methods.

00:53:53.029 --> 00:53:55.070 align:middle line:84%
LISA: Do you think that's
the future of medicine?

00:53:55.070 --> 00:53:57.284 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: I think so.

00:53:57.284 --> 00:53:59.450 align:middle line:84%
And not alternative medicine,
because alternative is

00:53:59.450 --> 00:54:00.980 align:middle line:90%
either modern medicine or not.

00:54:00.980 --> 00:54:03.460 align:middle line:84%
You have to integrate the
best of the two systems.

00:54:03.460 --> 00:54:05.930 align:middle line:84%
LISA: And that's
combination of--

00:54:05.930 --> 00:54:08.736 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: Western medicine,
some Eastern, and even

00:54:08.736 --> 00:54:09.860 align:middle line:90%
some other Native American.

00:54:09.860 --> 00:54:12.740 align:middle line:10%
There's a physician,
Luis Medrano,

00:54:12.740 --> 00:54:15.290 align:middle line:10%
who's a well trained physician
from Stanford Medical

00:54:15.290 --> 00:54:20.900 align:middle line:10%
School, who uses narratives,
like the Navajo culture

00:54:20.900 --> 00:54:21.760 align:middle line:10%
that he came from.

00:54:21.760 --> 00:54:22.350 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Stories?

00:54:22.350 --> 00:54:23.308 align:middle line:90%
MARTINEZ: Storytelling.

00:54:23.308 --> 00:54:26.050 align:middle line:84%
And storytelling can
have a healing effect.

00:54:26.050 --> 00:54:27.622 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Yes, you tell
a lot of stories.

00:54:27.622 --> 00:54:28.580 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: That's right.

00:54:28.580 --> 00:54:29.600 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Absolutely.

00:54:29.600 --> 00:54:31.516 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: But we do have
to get away from what

00:54:31.516 --> 00:54:33.690 align:middle line:10%
I call conveyor belt medicine.

00:54:33.690 --> 00:54:36.730 align:middle line:84%
The cubicles and, oh, yes, a
psychiatrist on the average

00:54:36.730 --> 00:54:38.564 align:middle line:84%
will see a person
for eight minutes.

00:54:38.564 --> 00:54:39.980 align:middle line:84%
And they look at
vegetative signs.

00:54:39.980 --> 00:54:41.390 align:middle line:84%
And they're, OK, we're
going to change this.

00:54:41.390 --> 00:54:42.410 align:middle line:90%
We'll be back.

00:54:42.410 --> 00:54:43.730 align:middle line:90%
You can't heal like that.

00:54:43.730 --> 00:54:44.200 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't work.

00:54:44.200 --> 00:54:46.040 align:middle line:84%
LISA: But that's the way
the insurance companies are

00:54:46.040 --> 00:54:46.600 align:middle line:90%
forcing the doctors to be.

00:54:46.600 --> 00:54:47.540 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: Absolutely.

00:54:47.540 --> 00:54:51.020 align:middle line:10%
And a doctor will graduate
from medical school

00:54:51.020 --> 00:54:53.960 align:middle line:10%
with an average
debt of $200,000.

00:54:53.960 --> 00:54:55.590 align:middle line:10%
What are they going to do?

00:54:55.590 --> 00:54:58.020 align:middle line:10%
They have to buy
into the system.

00:54:58.020 --> 00:55:00.840 align:middle line:84%
And they have to charge,
because you have to live.

00:55:00.840 --> 00:55:02.460 align:middle line:84%
So it's the system
that has to change.

00:55:02.460 --> 00:55:03.410 align:middle line:90%
How does it change?

00:55:03.410 --> 00:55:05.150 align:middle line:84%
The free market can change
it to a certain degree,

00:55:05.150 --> 00:55:07.149 align:middle line:84%
because you don't like
what this person's doing,

00:55:07.149 --> 00:55:09.740 align:middle line:84%
you start taking
responsibility for your health.

00:55:09.740 --> 00:55:12.200 align:middle line:84%
And then you go to
other integrative kind

00:55:12.200 --> 00:55:14.420 align:middle line:90%
of systems that are going on.

00:55:14.420 --> 00:55:17.600 align:middle line:10%
A good friend of
mine is a physician

00:55:17.600 --> 00:55:20.630 align:middle line:10%
and he's teaching
people, in addition

00:55:20.630 --> 00:55:22.430 align:middle line:10%
to whatever medical
intervention he does,

00:55:22.430 --> 00:55:24.650 align:middle line:10%
he teaches them a
lifestyle that's

00:55:24.650 --> 00:55:26.350 align:middle line:10%
incompatible with the illness--

00:55:26.350 --> 00:55:26.740 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Incompatible?

00:55:26.740 --> 00:55:27.960 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: Incompatible
with the illness.

00:55:27.960 --> 00:55:28.350 align:middle line:90%
LISA: In what way?

00:55:28.350 --> 00:55:29.160 align:middle line:90%
What do you mean?

00:55:29.160 --> 00:55:30.951 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: For example,
if you're a diabetic

00:55:30.951 --> 00:55:32.600 align:middle line:84%
and you take
medication, what would

00:55:32.600 --> 00:55:34.380 align:middle line:84%
be incompatible with
being a diabetic?

00:55:34.380 --> 00:55:36.960 align:middle line:84%
One of the things that you
can do is-- well, good health.

00:55:36.960 --> 00:55:38.630 align:middle line:10%
But one of the
things about diabetes

00:55:38.630 --> 00:55:44.486 align:middle line:10%
is that there's a certain
amount of unresolved anger.

00:55:44.486 --> 00:55:46.610 align:middle line:10%
And if you ask the person,
yeah, I don't get angry.

00:55:46.610 --> 00:55:47.410 align:middle line:90%
I don't get angry.

00:55:47.410 --> 00:55:50.210 align:middle line:84%
When you don't get angry, you
secrete a lot of endorphins.

00:55:50.210 --> 00:55:52.652 align:middle line:10%
And there's some research
beginning to look at this.

00:55:52.652 --> 00:55:54.360 align:middle line:10%
And when you secrete
a lot of endorphins,

00:55:54.360 --> 00:55:56.810 align:middle line:10%
which is good, but
too much is not good,

00:55:56.810 --> 00:55:58.460 align:middle line:10%
you anesthetize the anger.

00:55:58.460 --> 00:56:00.650 align:middle line:84%
And high levels of
endorphins begins

00:56:00.650 --> 00:56:02.810 align:middle line:84%
to affect the
metabolism of glucose.

00:56:02.810 --> 00:56:03.930 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Sugar.

00:56:03.930 --> 00:56:06.270 align:middle line:84%
MARTINEZ: So there's
some correlation there.

00:56:06.270 --> 00:56:07.070 align:middle line:90%
LISA: Interesting.

00:56:07.070 --> 00:56:11.000 align:middle line:10%
So are you saying to diabetics
to have anger management?

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:13.050 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: To be able to
express what they feel--

00:56:13.050 --> 00:56:13.850 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Healthily--

00:56:13.850 --> 00:56:15.620 align:middle line:10%
MARTINEZ: To express it healthy.

00:56:15.620 --> 00:56:16.835 align:middle line:10%
To let go of the control.

00:56:16.835 --> 00:56:19.340 align:middle line:10%


00:56:19.340 --> 00:56:22.850 align:middle line:10%
And this is for people who
are afraid of family history.

00:56:22.850 --> 00:56:26.670 align:middle line:10%
So you have a family
history of diabetes type 2.

00:56:26.670 --> 00:56:27.470 align:middle line:10%
What do you do?

00:56:27.470 --> 00:56:29.690 align:middle line:10%
You begin to look for
people in your family

00:56:29.690 --> 00:56:33.020 align:middle line:10%
who didn't have diabetes type 2.

00:56:33.020 --> 00:56:35.850 align:middle line:10%
And find out what were the
causes of their health.

00:56:35.850 --> 00:56:36.650 align:middle line:10%
LISA: Good point.

00:56:36.650 --> 00:56:37.451 align:middle line:10%
That's the reverse.

00:56:37.451 --> 00:56:38.250 align:middle line:10%
Wow.

00:56:38.250 --> 00:56:39.720 align:middle line:10%
What a great conversation.

00:56:39.720 --> 00:56:45.140 align:middle line:84%
And we this is so terrific
that you have shed such light

00:56:45.140 --> 00:56:48.660 align:middle line:90%
on a reverse side of medicine.

00:56:48.660 --> 00:56:51.690 align:middle line:84%
You've shed light on the
health aspects of everything.

